News|location=Bangor, ME|date=2019-02-13}}\n* U.S. War Department, [http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html ''The War of the Rebellion'']: ''a Compilation of the [[Official Records of the American Civil War|Official Records]] of the Union and Confederate Armies''. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|American Civil War}}\n* [[List of Maine Civil War units]]\n* [[Maine in the American Civil War]]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061229160318/http://www.state.me.us/sos/arc/archives/military/civilwar/3meinf.htm State of Maine Civil War Records Website]\n*[http://www.mainememory.net/bin/Detail?ln=4127 Photograph of the 17th Maine Infantry from the Maine Memory Network]\n\n[[Category:Maine Civil War regiments|17th Maine Volunteer Infantry Regiment]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Maine]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n\n\n{{AmericanCivilWar-unit-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1865", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/17th_Regiment_Maine_Volunteer_Infantry"}
{"title_page": "Nathaniel Felton Houses", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Nathaniel Felton Houses\n| nrhp_type = \n| image = PeabodyMA NathanielFeltonSrHouse.jpg\n| caption = Nathaniel Felton Sr. House\n| location = [[Peabody, Massachusetts]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|42|32|44|N|70|57|40|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Massachusetts#USA\n| area = \n| built = ca. 1700\n| architect = Nathaniel Felton Sr.\n| architecture = \n| added = April 1, 1982\n| refnum = 82001882<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Nathaniel Felton Houses''' are a pair of historic houses at 43 and 47 Felton Street in [[Peabody, Massachusetts]].  The Peabody Historical Society owns and operates the homes as [[historic house museums]].\n[[File:Nathaniel Felton, Jr., House.jpg|alt=Nathaniel Felton Jr. House|left|thumb|Nathaniel Felton Jr. House]]\nThe house of [[Nathaniel Felton|Nathaniel Felton Sr.]], at 47 Felton Street, was built ca. 1700<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peabodyhistorical.org/properties/|title=Properties {{!}} Peabody Historical Society|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>.  The house of his son, Nathaniel Felton Jr., was built at a different location, and moved to its present location by his grandson.<ref name=JR>{{cite web|url=http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=PEA.8|title=MACRIS inventory record for Nathaniel Felton Jr. House|publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts|accessdate=2014-01-20}}</ref>\n\nThe houses were listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1982.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Essex County, Massachusetts]]\n*[[List of the oldest buildings in Massachusetts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131026150320/http://peabodyhistorical.org/properties.asp#senior Nathaniel Felton Senior & Junior Houses] \u2013 Peabody Historical Society\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Massachusetts}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1644]]\n\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Museums in Essex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Houses in Peabody, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Essex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1644 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n\n\n{{EssexCountyMA-NRHP-stub}}\n{{Massachusetts-museum-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = Nathaniel Felton Houses\n| nrhp_type = \n| image = PeabodyMA NathanielFeltonSrHouse.jpg\n| caption = Nathaniel Felton Sr. House\n| location = [[Peabody, Massachusetts]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|42|32|44|N|70|57|40|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Massachusetts#USA\n| area =\n| built = 1644\n| architect = Nathaniel Felton Sr.\n| architecture =\n| added = April 1, 1982\n| refnum = 82001882<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Nathaniel Felton Houses''' are a pair of historic houses at 43 and 47 Felton Street in [[Peabody, Massachusetts]].  The Peabody Historical Society owns and operates the homes as [[historic house museums]].\n[[File:Nathaniel Felton, Jr., House.jpg|alt=Nathaniel Felton Jr. House|left|thumb|Nathaniel Felton Jr. House]]\nThe house of [[Nathaniel Felton|Nathaniel Felton Sr.]], at 47 Felton Street, was built in 1644, and is the oldest house in Peabody.<ref name=SR>{{cite web|url=http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=PEA.7|title=MACRIS inventory record for Nathaniel Felton Sr. House|publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts|accessdate=2014-01-20}}</ref>  The house of his son, Nathaniel Felton Jr., was built in 1683 at a different location, and moved to its present location by his grandson.<ref name=JR>{{cite web|url=http://mhc-macris.net/Details.aspx?MhcId=PEA.8|title=MACRIS inventory record for Nathaniel Felton Jr. House|publisher=Commonwealth of Massachusetts|accessdate=2014-01-20}}</ref>\n\nThe houses were listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1982.<ref name=\"nris\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Essex County, Massachusetts]]\n*[[List of the oldest buildings in Massachusetts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20131026150320/http://peabodyhistorical.org/properties.asp#senior Nathaniel Felton Senior & Junior Houses] \u2013 Peabody Historical Society\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Massachusetts}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1644]]\n\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Museums in Essex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Houses in Peabody, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in Essex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1644 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n\n\n{{EssexCountyMA-NRHP-stub}}\n{{Massachusetts-museum-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Old houses", "label": "safe", "comment": "Citation from reliable source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nathaniel_Felton_Houses"}
{"title_page": "2015 Tokyo Marathon", "text_new": "{{Infobox athletics competition\n|competition = 9th Tokyo Marathon\n|image = 2015 Tokyo Marathon - leading men.jpg\n|caption = The leading men with pacemakers during the race\n|venue = [[Tokyo]], Japan\n|dates = 22 February\n|gold = [[Endeshaw Negesse]] (2:06:00)<br>[[Berhane Dibaba]] (2:23:15)\n|prev = [[2014 Tokyo Marathon|2014]]\n|next = [[2016 Tokyo Marathon|2016]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2015 [[Tokyo Marathon]]''' ({{lang-ja|\u6771\u4eac\u30de\u30e9\u30bd\u30f3 2015}}) was the ninth edition of the annual [[marathon]] race in [[Tokyo]], Japan and was held on Sunday, 22 February. An [[IAAF Gold Label Road Race]], it was the first [[World Marathon Majors]] event to be held that year and represented the third occasion that the Tokyo race was part of the elite-level marathon series.\n\n[[File:2015 Tokyo Marathon fun runner.jpg|thumb|A fun runner during the race, wearing a [[Donald Duck]] costume]]\n\nThe elite race winners were both from Ethiopia \u2013 the first such time that athletes from the same nation won the men's and women's division. [[Endeshaw Negesse]] was just over twenty seconds off the course record with 2:06:00 hours while [[Berhane Dibaba]] took the women's title in 2:23:15. It was the first major marathon win for both athletes, although Berhane Dibaba had been runner-up in Tokyo the previous year. The reigning Olympic and world champion [[Stephen Kiprotich]] was runner-up in the men's race and [[Dickson Chumba]] was third, failing to defend his title. The women's podium was rounded out by [[Helah Kiprop]] (2014 winner of the [[Seoul International Marathon]]) and reigning Olympic champion [[Tiki Gelana]]. The 2014 women's champion, [[Tirfi Tsegaye]] did not return to defend her title. The fastest home athletes both finished in seventh position overall: [[Masato Imai (runner)|Masato Imai]] in the men's and [[Madoka Ogi]] in the women's division.<ref>Nakamura, Ken (2015-02-22). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/2015-tokyo-marathon-report Ethiopian duo Negesse and Dibaba win at the 2015 Tokyo Marathon ]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2015-02-23.</ref>\n\nAs in the previous year, the [[wheelchair race]] was principally a national affair. [[Wakako Tsuchida]] defended her title while [[Kota Hokinoue]]\u2014winner at the [[2014 Berlin Marathon]]\u2014won the men's wheelchair race for the first time.\n\n==Results==\n[[File:2015 Tokyo Marathon - leading men2.jpg|thumb|The leading pack of elite men during the race ([[Tsegaye Kebede]] is centre wearing number 2)]]\n===Elite men===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Position \n! Athlete \n! Nationality\n! Time\n|-\n|  align=center|{{gold1}}  || [[Endeshaw Negesse]] || {{ETH}} || 2:06:00\n|-\n|  align=center|{{silver2}}  || [[Stephen Kiprotich]] || {{UGA}} || 2:06:33\n|-\n|  align=center|{{bronze3}} || [[Dickson Chumba]] || {{KEN}} || 2:06:34\n|-\n| align=center|4 || [[Shumi Dechasa]] || {{BHR}} || 2:07:20\n|-\n| align=center|5 || [[Peter Some]] || {{KEN}} || 2:07:22\n|-\n| align=center|6 || [[Markos Geneti]] || {{ETH}} || 2:07:25\n|-\n| align=center|7 || [[Masato Imai (runner)|Masato Imai]] || {{JPN}} || 2:07:39\n|-\n| align=center|8 || [[Tsegaye Kebede]] || {{ETH}} || 2:07:58\n|-\n| align=center|9 || [[Hiroaki Sano]] || {{JPN}} || 2:09:12\n|-\n| align=center|10 || [[Benjamin Ngandu]] || {{KEN}} || 2:09:19\n|-\n| align=center|11 || [[Koji Gokaya]] || {{JPN}} || 2:09:21\n|-\n| align=center|12 || [[Yared Asmerom]] || {{ERI}} || 2:09:41\n|}\n;Other notable performers\n*[[Ryo Yamamoto]]: 17th, 2:12:46\n*[[Yuki Sato (athlete)|Yuki Sato]]: 20th, 2:14:15\n*[[Arata Fujiwara]]: 37th, 2:19:40\n\n===Elite women===\n[[File:2015 Tokyo Marathon - leading women.jpg|thumb|The leading women in the marathon race (Tiki Gelana is left of centre, wearing number 31)]]\n[[File:2015 Tokyo Marathon - Japanese runners.jpg|thumb|Elite Japanese women during the race]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Position \n! Athlete \n! Nationality\n! Time\n|-\n|  align=center|{{