 {{small|(7, 9)}}, mixing {{small|(1, 5, 9)}}\n* [[Tchad Blake]] \u2013\u00a0mixing {{small|(2\u20134, 6, 7, 10\u201313)}}\n* [[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013\u00a0mastering\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs master|1719775}}\n*{{Musicbrainz release group|a9ee533f-8871-4f62-a6bb-91eb264abc90}}\n\n{{Fiona Apple}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Sebastian Steinberg]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded in a home studio]]\n[[Category:Epic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Fiona Apple albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| cover        = Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters.png\n| alt          = A black-and-white close-up of Apple with a very thick black border that has hand-drawn lightning bolts on either side and the artist and title written in a hand-drawn purple font\n| released     = {{Start date|2020|4|17}}\n| recorded     = July 2015&nbsp;\u2013 March 2020\n| studio       =\n* Apple's house ([[Los Angeles]])\n* Stanley (Los Angeles)\n* [[Sonic Ranch]] ([[Tornillo, Texas]])\n* [[Dave Way|Waystation]] (Los Angeles)\n| genre        = <!-- Please do not add genres without a reliable source -->\n| length       = 51:54\n| label        = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| producer     = \n* Fiona Apple\n* Amy Aileen Wood with [[Sebastian Steinberg]]\n* [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| prev_title   = [[The Idler Wheel...]]\n| prev_year    = 2012\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n}}\n\n'''''Fetch the Bolt Cutters''''' is the fifth studio album by American singer-songwriter [[Fiona Apple]]. It was released on April 17, 2020, Apple's first release since ''[[The Idler Wheel...]]'' in 2012. Apple began recording the album in 2015, producing and performing it alongside Amy Aileen Wood, [[Sebastian Steinberg]] and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]. It features a percussive and idiosyncratic sound, lyrically exploring freedom from oppression and Apple's relationships with women. The album received universal critical acclaim upon its release, and is currenty the highest-rated album of all time on review aggregator [[Metacritic]].\n\n==Background and recording==\nIn 2012, Apple began conceptualising a new album, considering a [[concept album]] based on her home in [[Venice Beach]] or the [[Pando (tree)|Pando]] in Utah.\n\nIn February 2015, she began rehearsals for the album with band members [[Sebastian Steinberg]], Amy Aileen Wood and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]].<ref name=\"VultureProfile\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters.html|title=Allow Fiona Apple to Reintroduce Herself|last=Handler|first=Rachel|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> They began writing and rehearsing in Apple's [[Venice Beach]] home studio, using home-made percussive objects and chanting as they marched around the house.<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2020/03/23/fiona-apples-art-of-radical-sensitivity|title=Fiona Apple's Art of Radical Sensitivity|last=Nussbaum|first=Emily|author-link=Emily Nussbaum|website=[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]|date=March 16, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn July, they began recording the album, spending three weeks at the [[Sonic Ranch]] studio in rural Texas, with little success. A few months later, after returning to Venice Beach, they began making progress, with Apple recording long takes consisting of instruments being hit against surfaces and objects. Apple's vocals were unedited, and the album developed a highly percussive sound.<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/><ref name=\"newyorker\"/> As well as Apple's home, recording sessions took place at Stanley Recordings and at engineer [[Dave Way]]'s private studio, Waystation.<ref name=\"Credits\"/>\n\nBy July 2019, Apple had begun mixing the album. In September, the process began to slow down, with Apple developing doubts about the album.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> At this time, the artist first mentioned work on her new project in an interview with ''[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]'', explaining that she was still working hard on her next album which should have been released \"a million years ago\" and was hoping to put it out in 2020. She also admitted to being reclusive due to ongoing recording sessions at her Venice Beach house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/09/fiona-apple-is-still-calling-bullshit.html|title=Fiona Apple Is Still Calling Bullshit|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, she played the mixes to her band members, whose positive response brought Apple back on track.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> In an interview that month, she said that the album process was in its final stages, with the only things left being \"artwork and stuff\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-soon/|title=Fiona Apple says new album will \"be done soon\"|last=Bacior|first=Robin|website=Consequence of Sound|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/01/fiona-apple-new-album-updates.html|title=15 Minutes With Fiona Apple|last=Handler|first=Rachel|website=Vulture|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, 2020, she revealed that she had finished recording.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/fiona-apple-reveals-her-new-album-is-finished-2622233|title=Fiona Apple reveals her new album is finished|last=Langford|first=Jackson|website=[[NME]]|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n===Musical style===\nThe album's sound is defined by percussion. Apple's characteristic piano-playing is still evident, but takes a more percussive form.<ref name=\"NYTReview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/17/arts/music/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters.html|title=Fiona Apple Is Back and Unbound: Let\u2019s Discuss|last1=Pareles|first1=Jon|author-link1=Jon Pareles|last2=Caramanica|first2=Jon|author-link2=Jon Caramanica|last3=Morris|first3=Wesley|author-link3=Wesley Morris|last4=Zoladz|first4=Lindsay|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Stereogum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2081382/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review/franchises/premature-evaluation/|title=Premature Evaluation: Fiona Apple ''Fetch The Bolt Cutters''|last=Breihan|first=Tom|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Stereogum]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> As well as drum sets and traditional percussion, the album features the use of found objects as percussion, such as a metal butterfly and the bones of Apple's dog Janet.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/><ref name=\"Credits\"/> The experimental rhythms on the album evoke [[industrial music]] and are juxtaposed against more traditional melodies.<ref name=\"LA Times\"/> ''[[Stereogum]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s Tom Breihan argues that while percussive music is typically \"built around the idea of dancing, of guiding and channeling the rhythms of the human body\", the album instead \"plays as a wild, feverish attempt to mirror the chaos that goes on in the human mind when it\u2019s at its most overheated\"<ref name=\"Stereogum\"/>\n\nThe album often rejects [[popular music]]'s traditional verse-chorus structure. The unpredictable songs feature looped sections, sudden stops and tempo changes.<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/><ref name=\"LA Times\"/><ref name=\"newyorker\"/> Apple's long-time bassist [[Sebastian Steinberg]] compared the album to Apple's 2012 song \"Hot Knife\", describing it as \"very raw and unslick\".<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> It has been noted as less melancholy than Apple's past work, with the uptempo songs being described as \"funny, angry, and at times triumphant\".<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/> The album features frequent improvisation, as well as background noise such as the barking of dogs, largely as a result of its home recording. Apple's dog Mercy appears on the album, as well as [[Cara Delevigne]]'s Leo and Alfie, and Zelda Hallman's Maddie.<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/>\n\nOn the album, Apple approached her voice as a musical instrument, commenting: \"I have fun with my voice, but I\u2019m not trying to make it pretty all the time. I\u2019m not trying to convince anybody I\u2019m a singer. It just turned out to be another instrument\".<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/> Breihan noted that Apple demonstrates \"a [[rapper]]\u2019s sense that words can be music\",<ref name=\"Stereogum\"/> while ''[[The Guardian]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Laura Barton]] highlighted the intimacy of Apple's vocals: \"half-conversational, half-self-mutters, allowing every scuff, breath and feral yelp\".<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> [[Jon Pareles]] and [[Wesley Morris]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' found that \"whether she\u2019s cooing with sarcastic solicitousness or rasping close to a scream, she articulates every word clearly, emoting but never losing control\".<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/>\n\nThe album defies genre categorisation, and critics have noted its originality.<ref name=\"Stereogum\"/><ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Nevertheless, it has been compared to the works of [[Joni Mitchell]],<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/><ref name=\"Observer\"/> [[Tom Waits]],<ref name=\"The Times\"/><ref name=\"NYTReview\"/><ref name=\"Observer\"/> [[Nina Simone]],<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/><ref name=\"LA Times\"/> and [[Kate Bush]],<ref name=\"The Times\"/><ref name=\"NYTReview\"/> who is quoted on the title track.<ref name=\"Observer\"/>\n\n===Lyrics and themes===\nLyrically, Apple identified the album's main theme as \"not being afraid to speak,\"<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> with Barton similarly recognising \"a refusal to be silenced\".<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Apple later said that this was an oversimplification, elaborating that \"it's about breaking out of whatever prison you\u2019ve allowed yourself to live in,\" and pinpointing the message as: \"Fetch the fucking bolt cutters and get yourself out of the situation you\u2019re in\".<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/> Pareles found that the album explored \"both past and present injuries: bullying, sexual assault, destructive mind games, romantic debacles, [Apple's] own fears and compulsions and the people who have taken advantage of them\".<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/> The album explores freedom,<ref name=\"Observer\"/> with Breihan writing that \"we can hear the euphoria of a great unburdening\".<ref name=\"Stereogum\"/> The album has also been identified as Apple's most humorous album.<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/>\n\nAnother theme Apple explores on the album are her complex social relationships with other women.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> Apple commented that these relationships began to suffer in middle school,<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/> and the album features Apple trying to make peace \"the sorts of women that society has always deemed her 'competition'\", such as subsequent girlfriends of her exes.<ref name=\"NYTReview\"/> Apple summarised this idea as \"not letting men pit us against each other or keep us separate from each other so they can control the message\".<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/>\n\n==Release==\nOn March 16, 2020, Apple announced the album and its title in an extensive ''[[New Yorker (magazine)|New Yorker]]'' profile.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/> At the start of April, she announced that the album was set to be released digitally on April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-releasing-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-this-month/|title=Fiona Apple Releasing New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' This Month|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 1, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Epic Records]] had planned to release the album in October, due to promotional limitations brought by the [[impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the arts and cultural heritage|coronavirus pandemic]]. However, Apple pushed to release the album early, both for the benefit of listeners who were under [[self-isolation]], and so she could avoid stressful press commitments.<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/> Critics have commented on the timeliness of releasing the album during the pandemic, finding thematic relevance in its exploration of confinement, and comparing Apple's reclusiveness to the widespread self-isolation restrictions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-album-of-the-pandemic.html|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' Is the Unofficial Album of the Pandemic|last=Adams|first=Sam|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review/610051/|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s Survival Guide to Isolation|last=Kornhaber|first=Spencer|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Boston Globe\"/>\n\n=== Artwork and title ===\nThe album's artwork was designed by band member [[Dav\u00edd Garza]], following the decision to release the album early. Apple sent him a photo she had taken of herself \"two or three\" years earlier, and saved as a potential cover photo. On the choice of photograph, she commented: \"That face is very much me. I just wanted to be like, 'Hey, guess what? I\u2019m back! Here are some songs. Want to listen to the music, huh? Hi, hi, hi, hi.'\"<ref name=\"VultureProfile\"/>\n\nThe title, ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'', is a quote from the British-Irish crime drama television series ''[[The Fall (TV series)|The Fall]]'', where the protagonist, a sex-crimes investigator portrayed by [[Gillian Anderson]], recites the phrase while investigating a crime scene where a woman was tortured.<ref name=\"newyorker\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| AOTY = 95/100<ref name=\"aoty\">{{cite web |title=Fiona Apple - Fetch the Bolt Cutters - Reviews |url=https://www.albumoftheyear.org/album/224348-fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters.php |publisher=Album of The Year |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| ADM = 9.1/10<ref name=\"adm\">{{cite web |title=Fetch The Bolt Cutters by Fiona Apple reviews|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/11368/Fiona-Apple-Fetch-The-Bolt-Cutters.aspx |publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]] |accessdate=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| MC = 100/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/fetch-the-bolt-cutters/fiona-apple|title=Fetch the Bolt Cutters by Fiona Apple Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev1score = A<ref name=\"The A.V. Club\">{{cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/with-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-fiona-apple-hits-a-zenith-1842908893|title=With Fetch The Bolt Cutters, Fiona Apple hits a zenith of liberation and experimentation|last=Corcoran|first=Nina|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Consequence of Sound]]''\n| rev2score = A<ref>{{cite web |last1=Monokandilos |first1=Irene |title=Album Review: Fiona Apple's Fetch the Bolt Cutters Is an Untethered Masterpiece |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/04/album-review-fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters/ |website=[[Consequence of Sound]] |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/17/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 a glorious eruption|last=Barton|first=Laura|author-link=Laura Barton|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev4score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-new-album-tracklist-stream-a9468761.html|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: A witty, wonderful album laced with defiance|last=Pollard|first=Alexandra|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-2648715|title=Fiona Apple \u2013 \u2018Fetch The Bolt Cutters\u2019 review: an intoxicating listen that will cut deep|last=Krol|first=Charlotte|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[NME]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Observer]]''\n| rev6score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Observer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/18/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-fourth-album-strange-exceptional|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2013 a strange, exceptional record|last=Empire|first=Kitty|author-link=Kitty Empire|date=April 18, 2020|website=[[The Observer]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev7score = 10/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters Album Review|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-2-984926/|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s \u2018Fetch the Bolt Cutters\u2019 Is a Triumphant Statement of Self-Discovery and Solidarity\n|last=Shaffer|first=Claire|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''\n| rev9score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Telegraph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/music/what-to-listen-to/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review-proof-one-greatest-songwriters/|title=Fiona Apple, Fetch the Bolt Cutters review: a masterpiece for the #MeToo era|last=McCormick|first=Neil|author-link=Neil McCormick|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[The Times]]''\n| rev10score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"The Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-she-has-kate-bushs-poetry-and-the-spirit-of-tom-waits-j088600fq/|title=Fiona Apple: Fetch the Bolt Cutters review \u2014 she has Kate Bush\u2019s poetry and the spirit of Tom Waits|last=Hodgkinson|first=Will|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[The Times]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' was met with widespread acclaim, with many critics deeming it an instant classic, a masterpiece, and Apple's best work to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review-roundup.html|title=Critics Agree: Fiona Apple\u2019s ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' Is an Instant Classic|last=Curto|first=Justin|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> At review aggregator [[Metacritic]], the release received a [[weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 100 out of 100, based on 17 reviews,<ref name=\"MC\" /> making it the highest-rated non-retrospective album in the website's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/browse/albums/score/metascore/all/filtered?sort=desc|title=Best Music and Albums of All Time|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref> It is also the second highest-rated album on [[AnyDecentMusic?]], with a rating of 9.1/10.<ref name=\"adm\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/chart/AllTime.aspx|title=All Time|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> [[Album of the Year (website)|Album of the Year]] assigned it a 95 out of 100.<ref name=\"aoty\" />\n\nThe album was awarded ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'''s  first perfect score since [[Kanye West]]'s ''[[My Beautiful Dark Twisted Fantasy]]'' in 2010, with Jenn Pelly writing, \"No music has ever sounded quite like it.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/fiona-apples-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-scores-a-10-on-pitchfork/ |title=Pitchfork gives Fiona Apple's new album a 10 |last=Hatfield |first=Amanda |date=April 17, 2020 |website=[[BrooklynVegan]] |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/pitchfork-fiona-apple-first-perfect-score-decade/ |title=Pitchfork just gave Fiona Apple their first perfect score in almost a decade |last=Jenke |first=Brittany |date=April 17, 2020 |website=Tone Deaf |publisher=The Brag |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> [[Neil McCormick]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' described it as \"a masterpiece for the [[Me Too movement|#MeToo]] era\", writing that it \"feels about as real as music can be\".<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> [[Laura Barton]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' commented on the album's \"refusal to be silenced\", writing: \"The result is that this seems not so much an album as a sudden glorious eruption; after eight long years, an urgent desire to be heard\".<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Mikael Wood of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote of the \"stunning intimacy of the material here\u2014a rich text to scour\", adding \"you'd need to go back to the later parts of [[Nina Simone]]\u2019s catalog to find another pop vocalist as eager as Apple is to make such a show of unprettiness.\"<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-04-16/fiona-apple-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-review|title=Fiona Apple\u2019s stunningly intimate new album makes a bold show of unprettiness|last=Wood|first=Mikael|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> Judy Berman of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' similarly praised the album for its \"conversational tone, manifested in Apple\u2019s talky delivery as well as in lyrics that scan as prose more often than poetry, [which] creates a rare intimacy\", and commented that \"As beautiful as the melodies and the epiphanies they carry often are, the songs are not what you would call \u2018pretty.\u2019...Yet ''Bolt Cutters''\u00a0wouldn\u2019t be the extraordinary experiment in aural and lyrical honesty that it is if it sounded too polished\".<ref name=\"Time Magazine\">{{cite web|url=https://time.com/5823031/fiona-apple-fetch-bolt-cutters-review/|title=Fetch the Bolt Cutters Is Raw, Introspective and Everything We Need Out of a Fiona Apple Album|last=Berman|first=Judy|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> \n\n[[Maura Johnston]] of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' applauded the album for its \"matter-of-fact depictions of everyday brutality\", and added that \"even [during] the most intense moments of ''Fetch,'' her lyrics retain a playfulness that acts as a ballast.\" She also commended Apple's \"husky [[alto]]\", which \"remains the focal point, launching into melodies that are instantly sticky as effortlessly as it engages in tensely rhythmic ''[[Sprechstimme]]''.\"<ref name=\"Boston Globe\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/16/arts/fiona-apple-makes-defiance-sound-exhilarating-fetch-bolt-cutters/|title=Fiona Apple makes defiance sound exhilarating on \u2018Fetch the Bolt Cutters\u2019|last=Johnston|first=Maura|author-link=Maura Johnston|date=April 16, 2020|website=[[Boston Globe]]|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref> ''[[The Observer]]'''s [[Kitty Empire]] described the album as \"a strange and exceptional record, even within the context of an uncommon career\".<ref name=\"Observer\"/> Patrick Ryan of ''[[USA Today]]'' wrote the album \"simmers with defiance, dark wit and quiet rage\", describing it as \"a dense and richly poetic\u00a0masterpiece from one of music's best modern storytellers\" with \"razor-sharp statements and evocative lyrics that reveal themselves in every new listen\".<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/04/17/fetch-bolt-cutters-review-fiona-apple/5128604002/|title=Album review: Fiona Apple's 'Fetch the Bolt Cutters' is a blistering, emotional triumph|last=Ryan|first=Patrick|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[USA Today]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|headline = ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'' track listing\n| all_writing = [[Fiona Apple]]\n| title1 = I Want You to Love Me\n| length1 = 3:57\n| title2 = Shameika\n| length2 = 4:08\n| title3 = Fetch the Bolt Cutters\n| length3 = 4:58\n| title4 = Under the Table\n| length4 = 3:21\n| title5 = Relay\n| length5 = 4:49\n| title6 = Rack of His\n| length6 = 3:42\n| title7 = Newspaper\n| length7 = 5:32\n| title8 = Ladies\n| note8 = music composed by [[Sebastian Steinberg]] and [[Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n| length8 = 5:25\n| title9 = Heavy Balloon\n| length9 = 3:26\n| title10 = Cosmonauts\n| length10 = 3:59\n| title11 = For Her\n| length11 = 2:43\n| title12 = Drumset\n| length12 = 2:40\n| title13 = On I Go\n| length13 = 3:09\n| total_length = 51:49\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''.<ref name=\"Credits\">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/fiona-apple-shares-new-album-fetch-the-bolt-cutters-listen-and-read-the-full-credits/|title=Fiona Apple Shares New Album ''Fetch the Bolt Cutters'': Listen and Read the Full Credits|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=April 17, 2020|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|access-date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n'''Band'''\n* [[Fiona Apple]] \u2013\u00a0vocals {{small|(all tracks)}}, piano {{small|(1, 2, 4, 10)}}, [[Casio]] drums {{small|(1)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 3, 5\u20137, 9, 10, 13)}}, background vocals {{small|(2\u20135, 7\u201313)}}, drums {{small|(3, 5\u20137, 9, 11, 13)}}, metal butterfly {{small|(3)}}, [[Mellotron]] {{small|(6, 12)}}, electronic drums {{small|(7)}}, timpani {{small|(7)}}, [[Wurlitzer electric piano|Wurlitzer]] {{small|(8)}}, Casio {{small|(9)}}, bells {{small|(9)}}, chair {{small|(12)}}\n* [[Sebastian Steinberg]] \u2013\u00a0bass {{small|(1\u201310, 12, 13)}}, drums {{small|(1)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 5, 9)}}, [[Autoharp#Electric autoharp|electric autoharp]] {{small|(10, 13)}}, acoustic 12-string guitar {{small|(10)}}, slide guitar {{small|(10)}}, background vocals {{small|(12)}}, lighter on Wurlitzer {{small|(12)}}, harp {{small|(12)}}, watertower {{small|(13)}}, stomps {{small|(13)}}, breathing {{small|(13)}}\n* Amy Aileen Wood \u2013 drums {{small|(1\u201310, 12, 13)}}, percussion {{small|(2, 4, 5, 9, 10, 13)}}, loops {{small|(10)}}\n* [[Dav\u00edd Garza]] \u2013\u00a0[[vibraphone|vibes]] {{small|(4, 8)}}, percussion {{small|(5, 8, 9, 12, 13)}}, guitar {{small|(6, 7)}}, background vocals {{small|(8, 12)}}, Mellotron {{small|(8)}}, piano {{small|(10)}}, electric guitar {{small|(10)}}, Wurlitzer {{small|(10)}}, organ {{small|(12)}}, watertower {{small|(13)}}\n\n'''Additional musicians'''\n{{div col}}\n* [[Best Coast|Bobb Bruno]] \u2013\u00a0special effects {{small|(2, 5)}}\n* [[Cara Delevingne]] \u2013 background vocals {{small|(3)}}\n* Mercy \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}, collar jangles and thrashing {{small|(5)}}\n* Maddie \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}\n* Leo \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}\n* Alfie \u2013\u00a0backing barks {{small|(3)}}\n* [[John Would]] \u2013\u00a0piano {{small|(4, 8)}}, Wurlitzer {{small|(4)}}, organ {{small|(4)}}\n* Little \u2013\u00a0collar jangles and thrashing {{small|(5)}}\n* [[Maude Maggart]] \u2013 background vocals {{small|(7, 8)}}\n* Winifred Lucky \u2013 background vocals {{small|(7)}}\n* Spencer Maggart \u2013\u00a0soft shoe stomp {{small|(13)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n'''Engineers'''\n{{div col}}\n* Amy Aileen Wood \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(1\u201310, 13)}}\n* John Would \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(1\u20135, 8\u201310, 12, 13)}}, mixing {{small|(8)}}\n* Fiona Apple \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(5\u20137, 9\u201311, 13)}}\n* [[Dave Way]] \u2013\u00a0recording {{small|(7, 9)}}, mixing {{small|(1, 5, 9)}}\n* [[Tchad Blake]] \u2013\u00a0mixing {{small|(2\u20134, 6, 7, 10\u201313)}}\n* [[Bob Ludwig]] \u2013\u00a0mastering\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs master|1719775}}\n*{{Musicbrainz release group|a9ee533f-8871-4f62-a6bb-91eb264abc90}}\n\n{{Fiona Apple}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dav\u00edd Garza]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Sebastian Steinberg]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded in a home studio]]\n[[Category:Epic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Fiona Apple albums]]\n", "name_user": "BethanyJohnsten", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fetch_the_Bolt_Cutters"}
{"title_page": "Gillingham, Kent", "text_new": "{{Other places|Gillingham (disambiguation){{!}}Gillingham}}\n{{short description|Town in Kent, England}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2013}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|official_name       = Gillingham\n|unitary_england     = [[Medway]]\n|lieutenancy_england = [[Kent]]\n|region              = South East England\n|country             = England\n|coordinates         = {{coord|51.385|0.550|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name   = Gillingham High Street (2) - geograph.org.uk - 639121.jpg\n|static_image_caption= High Street, Gillingham\n| population         = 104,157\n| population_ref     = (2011 census, including Rainham and its southern suburbs)<ref>https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/localarea?compare=1119883912</ref>\n|constituency_westminster= [[Gillingham and Rainham (UK Parliament constituency)|Gillingham and Rainham]]\n|post_town           = GILLINGHAM\n|postcode_area       = ME\n|postcode_district   = ME7\n|dial_code           = 01634\n|os_grid_reference   = TQ775675\n|london_distance     = 35.6mi\n}}\n'''Gillingham''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-uk-Gillingham(Kent).ogg|\u02c8|d\u0292|\u026a|l|\u026a|\u014b|\u0259m}} {{respell|JIL|ing|\u0259m}}) is a town in the county of [[Kent]] in [[South East England]]. For local government purposes it is also in the [[unitary authority]] of [[Medway]]. The town includes the settlements of [[Brompton, Medway|Brompton]], [[Hempstead, Kent|Hempstead]], [[Wigmore, Kent|Wigmore]], Parkwood, [[Rainham, Medway|Rainham]] which has its own significant retail and leisure hub, Rainham Mark and [[Twydall]].<!-- and [[Lidsing]] is not but used to be in the old Parish of Gillingham -->\n\nGillingham means a \"homestead of Gylla's family\", from [[Old English]] ''ham'' (\"village, homestead\") and ''ingas'' (\"family, followers\"), and was first recorded in the 10th century as ''Gyllingeham''.<ref>Also referred to in old texts as ''Jillyingham Water''.</ref> The town's name is pronounced with a soft 'g', compared to the hard 'g' used for [[Gillingham, Dorset]].\n\n==Status==\nGillingham became an [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] under the [[Local Government Act 1894]], gaining [[municipal borough]] status in 1903.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sharp|first1=Peter|title=Gillingham \u2013 from Rural District to Unitary Authority|url=http://gillinghamcorps.info/history.htm|website=The Salvation Army Gillingham Corps|accessdate=27 September 2015|date=2011}}</ref> John Robert Featherby was the first mayor of the Borough of Gillingham.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Featherby Family Tomb|url=http://www.historicmedway.co.uk/gillingham/st_mary_magdalene_grave_featherby.htm|website=Historic Medway|accessdate=27 September 2015|date=18 June 2012}}</ref> In 1928 [[Rainham, Kent|Rainham]] was added to the Gillingham Borough. Under the [[Local Government Act 1972]] it became a [[non-metropolitan district]]. It merged with the other Medway Towns (in the [[City of Rochester-upon-Medway]] district) in 1998 under the [[Local Government Commission for England (1992)|1990s UK local government reform]], to become part of the [[Medway]] unitary authority.\n\n===Town hall===\nThe Municipal Buildings in Canterbury Street were built as council offices for Gillingham Borough Council. They were opened by the Lord [[Mayor of London]], Sir [[George Broadbridge]], on 25 September 1937. The Lord Mayor was received at [[Gillingham Railway Station (Kent)|Gillingham Railway Station]] by a [[guard of honour]] of boys of [[HMS Arethusa (26)|HMS ''Arethusa'']]. Before the Second World War, air raid sirens were placed on the Municipal Buildings, and the local [[Civil Defence]] headquarters were in a single-storey building, to the rear of the car park. In about 1953, beneath part of the car park, Gillingham Borough Control Centre was built underground.\n\nWhen Gillingham Borough Council later merged with [[Rochester upon Medway]] to form the [[Medway|unitary Medway Authority]] in 1998, the buildings were still used as council offices and for meetings for several years afterwards. Later, Medway Council then moved into the former [[Lloyd's of London]] headquarters at Chatham Gun Wharf, and the Municipal Buildings were considered surplus to requirements. They were sold off in 2008 under a contract which turned them into a residential care home.<ref>John Clancy {{google books|zCD8AwAAQBAJ|Gillingham & Around Through Time|page=46}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe town grew along the road from Brompton on the great lines (military barracks), to the railway station. As such it was a linear development. Close by was the road along the shore line, linking The Strand, and the tiny village of Gillingham Green. Later, communities developed along the top road- Watling street \u2013 turnpike linking Chatham with Dover. All these communities merged into the town that is called today Gillingham.\n\n===Climate===\nGillingham experiences an [[oceanic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Cfb'') similar to almost all of the United Kingdom. Due to its southerly, sheltered, marine position near the European continent  the climate is among the warmest in the whole of England.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Gillingham, Kent 1981\u20132010\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan high C = 8.0\n|Feb high C = 8.1\n|Mar high C = 11.1\n|Apr high C = 13.8\n|May high C = 17.4\n|Jun high C = 20.4\n|Jul high C = 23.3\n|Aug high C = 22.7\n|Sep high C = 20.0\n|Oct high C = 15.7\n|Nov high C = 11.2\n|Dec high C = 8.4\n|year high C = \n|Jan low C = 2.6\n|Feb low C = 2.0\n|Mar low C = 3.9\n|Apr low C = 5.4\n|May low C = 8.3\n|Jun low C = 11.5\n|Jul low C = 13.8\n|Aug low C = 13.7\n|Sep low C = 11.4\n|Oct low C = 8.4\n|Nov low C = 5.2\n|Dec low C = 2.8\n|year low C = \n|Jan precipitation mm = 66.6\n|Feb precipitation mm = 40.5\n|Mar precipitation mm = 40.2\n|Apr precipitation mm = 44.9\n|May precipitation mm = 48.6\n|Jun precipitation mm = 40.9\n|Jul precipitation mm = 38.3\n|Aug precipitation mm = 44.0\n|Sep precipitation mm = 51.2\n|Oct precipitation mm = 60.1\n|Nov precipitation mm = 61.9\n|Dec precipitation mm = 57.0\n|year precipitation mm = \n|Jan rain days = 10.7\n|Feb rain days = 8.6\n|Mar rain days = 9.3\n|Apr rain days = 9.1\n|May rain days = 8.0\n|Jun rain days = 7.8\n|Jul rain days = 7.1\n|Aug rain days = 7.6\n|Sep rain days = 8.4\n|Oct rain days = 10.3\n|Nov rain days = 11.6\n|Dec rain days = 10.6\n|Jan sun = 44.0\n|Feb sun = 64.5\n|Mar sun = 106.8\n|Apr sun = 167.5\n|May sun = 185.1\n|Jun sun = 189.5\n|Jul sun = 208.0\n|Aug sun = 201.2\n|Sep sun = 152.6\n|Oct sun = 120.5\n|Nov sun = 67.7\n|Dec sun = 41.9\n|source 1 = [[Met Office]]<ref>{{cite web\n  | url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate/gillingham-fc#?tab=climateTables\n  | title=Gillingham FC Climatic Averages 1981\u20132010\n  | publisher=Met Office\n  | accessdate=23 December 2012}}</ref>\n|date=Dec 2012\n}}\n\n==History==\nThe name Gillingham is recorded in the [[Domesday book]] of 1086. It is said to have been named after a warlord, Gyllingas\u2014from the old English ''gyllan'', meaning \"to shout\". He was a notable man in Kent history as he led his warriors into battle screaming and shouting. At the time of the [[Norman Conquest]], Gillingham was a small [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]]. It was given to the half-brother of [[William I of England]], [[Odo, Bishop of Bayeux]], who rebuilt the parish church at Gillingham and constructed an Archbishop's Palace on land bordered by Grange Road, the ruins of which could still be seen in the last century. Gillingham itself, at the time, was a small hamlet, built around the parish church and surrounded by large farm-holdings, of which St. Mark's Parish formed part, being part of Brittain Farm.\n\n[[William Adams (sailor, born 1564)|William Adams]] mentioned Gillingham in his writings, saying: \"... two English\nmiles from Rochester and one mile from Chatham, where the King's ships do lie\". Adams was baptised at Gillingham Parish Church on 24 September 1564.<ref>WILL ADAMS: Gillingham\u2019s own Samurai.</ref>\n\n[[File:GillinghamStrand3117.JPG|thumb|right|The River Medway estuary at The Strand, Gillingham. The Kingsnorth power stations are on the opposite bank.]] The Strand was once owned by the Davenport family in 1635, the Davenport family included a Mayor of Gillingham,<ref name=amdavenport>[http://cityark.medway.gov.uk/query/results/?Mode=Search&PathList=&SearchWords=de0402_21&DateLis CityArt, Medway Council.] t</ref> pie makers and key holders of Gillingham. The Davenport family had a road named after them in 1920. The Davenport estate was in [[Ashford, Kent]]. The estate comprised around 15000 acres and was called The Davenport Manor. The Davenports lost the estate in 1889. The Davenport family were among the investors in the Chatham Dockyard.\nIn [[medieval]] times the part of Gillingham known as Grange was a limb of the [[Cinque Ports]]<ref>[http://www.medwaymemories.co.uk/?page_id=269 Stephen Rayner, \"A piece of Hastings \u2026 in a corner of Gillingham\", Medway memories.]</ref> and the maritime importance of the area continued until the late 1940s. Indeed, a large part of [[Chatham Dockyard]] lay within Gillingham: the [[dockyard]] started in Gillingham and, until the day it was closed in 1984, two-thirds of the then modern-day dockyard lay within the boundaries of Gillingham. The dockyard was founded by Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] on the site of the present gun wharf, the establishment being transferred to the present site about 1622. In 1667 a Dutch fleet sailed up the [[River Medway]] and, having landed at [[Queenborough]] on the [[Isle of Sheppey]] and laying siege to the fort at [[Sheerness]], invaded Gillingham in what became known as the [[raid on the Medway]]. The Dutch eventually retreated, but the incident caused great humiliation to the [[Royal Navy]].\n\nThe [[Seven Years' War]] began in 1756 and the government immediately gave orders for the defence of the dockyard; by 1758 the Chatham Lines of Defence were built. Over a mile long, they stretched across the neck of the dockyard [[peninsula]], from Chatham Reach, south of the dockyard, across to Gillingham Reach on the opposite side. One of the [[redoubt]]s on the Lines was at [[Fort Amherst|Amherst]]. The batteries faced away from the dockyard itself to forestall an attack from the landward side; the ships and shore-mounted guns on the river were considered sufficient to protect from that side. The lines of defence are now part of the [[Great Lines Heritage Park]] and also the Lower Lines Park (near [[MidKent College]], Gillingham Campus).\n[[File:GillinghamNavalWarMem2707.JPG|thumb|right|[[Chatham Naval Memorial]] on the Gillingham Great Lines]]\nWar with France began again in 1778, and once more it was necessary to strengthen the defences. Fort Amherst was the first to be improved; it was followed by work beginning in 1800 to add others at [[Fort Pitt, Kent|Fort Pitt]], Chatham, plus Fort Delce and [[Fort Clarence]] (both in [[Rochester, Kent|Rochester]]); later in the 19th century others were added, including one at [[Fort Darland]] in Gillingham. Within all these buildings a barracks was built to house the soldiers. All this work, and the expansion of the dockyard, meant that more homes were needed for the workers. The position of the Lines meant that this building could only happen beyond, and so New Brompton came into being. The population rose to 9,000 people by 1851.\n\nGillingham was still only a small village; eventually it, too, was swallowed up, and the name of the whole settlement changed to Gillingham. In the 1891 census its population was 27,809, and in 1901, it was 42,530.\n\nIn 1919, after World War I, a [[Chatham Naval Memorial|naval war memorial]] in the shape of a white stone obelisk was set up on the Great Lines, from where it can be seen for many miles.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Nigel Yates, ''Kent in the Twentieth Century''.</ref> Additional structures were added in 1945 to commemorate the dead of World War II. Similar monuments stand in the dockyard towns of [[Portsmouth]] and [[Plymouth]].\n\nIn 1919 the Frederick Burton family, which owned the old brick works, sold it and migrated to [[Auckland, New Zealand]] with their daughter Edith.\n\n===Disasters===\nGillingham has been the scene of two notable disasters: on 11 July 1929 a public demonstration by Gillingham Fire Brigade [[Gillingham Fair fire disaster|went wrong]], resulting in 15 fatalities;<ref>[http://www.medway.gov.uk/index/leisure/localhistory/timeline/17909/firemanswedding.htm Medway Council: \"Fireman's wedding disaster\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110173808/http://www.medway.gov.uk/index/leisure/localhistory/timeline/17909/firemanswedding.htm |date=10 January 2008 }}</ref> and in the [[1951 Gillingham bus disaster]], 24 Royal Marine cadets aged 10 to 13 were killed in a road accident.\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Gillingham Bus Depot - geograph.org.uk - 726224.jpg|thumb|[[Arriva Medway Towns]] bus depot in Gillingham]]\nThe main source of employment was at [[Chatham Dockyard]], two-thirds of which lay within the boundaries of Gillingham. When it ceased to be a [[naval base]] in 1984, there was significant unemployment. A [[World Heritage Site]] application is today planned for the Dockyard and its defences.<ref>See www.chathamworldheritage.co.uk</ref> Since the 1980s, Gillingham has rebuilt its economic base and the ''Gillingham Business Park'' was set up {{convert|3|mi|km}} from the town centre, to attract investments and diversify economic activity. The business park is one of the most popular business locations in North [[Kent]] and is located about two miles (3&nbsp;km) north of the [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2 motorway]]. Gillingham has a [[marina]] called ''Gillingham Marina''. Gillingham is an important retail centre serving a substantial part of Medway. The town has a large [[street market]] in the High Street on Saturdays and Mondays, and is the busiest in the whole of Medway.<ref>''Gillingham Town Centre Development Framework''</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Roads===\n\nThe [[Roman road]] now known as [[Watling Street]] passed through Gillingham; and until the opening of the Medway Towns bypass (the [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2 motorway]]) in the mid-1960s the same route was followed by the traffic on the A2 to Dover. That road had been [[toll road|turnpiked]] in 1730, as part of the London\u2013[[Canterbury]] coaching route.\n\nIn June 1996 the [[Medway Tunnel]] opened, giving Gillingham a second link to the M2 and Strood.\n\n===Railways===\n[[File:GillinghamRail3959.JPG|thumb|right|[[Gillingham (Kent) railway station|Gillingham Railway Depot]]]]\nThe [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway]] opened its [[Chatham Main Line|line]] between Chatham and [[Faversham]] on 25 January 1858; and a country station was opened here called New Brompton. This was to serve the dockyard labourers' homes that had sprung up during the [[Napoleonic Wars]]. A branch line led into the dockyard. The station later became [[Gillingham (Kent) railway station|Gillingham Railway Station]].\n\nServices improved significantly when in July 1939,<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Electric Railways \n |publisher='Stendec Systems' \n |year=2007 \n |url=http://www.electric-railways.co.uk/L2_DC_750_CR/1_general/g3_proj/prj-0d75-sr.html \n |accessdate=16 February 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928003510/http://www.electric-railways.co.uk/L2_DC_750_CR/1_general/g3_proj/prj-0d75-sr.html \n |archivedate=28 September 2007 \n}}</ref> Gillingham became the terminus of the [[Railway electrification in Great Britain|electrified]] system of the [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway]].\n\n===Trams===\nGillingham was served by an electric tram system operated by the [[Chatham and District Light Railways Company]] from 1902 to 1930.<ref name=\"trams\">{{cite book| author=Harley, Robert J.| year=1994| title=Maidstone and Chatham Tramways| publisher=Middleton Press|isbn=1-873793-40-5}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Gillingham Library - geograph.org.uk - 518041.jpg|thumb|Gillingham Library]]\n\n===Library===\nGillingham Public Library is located in the High Street.\n\n===Sport===\n[[File:GillinghamPriestfields3982.JPG|thumb|right|Priestfield Stadium, Home of the Gills]]\n[[File:The Black Lion Leisure Centre, Mill Rd - geograph.org.uk - 1243346.jpg|right|thumb| A view of former The Black Lion Leisure Centre (Now Medway Park), April 2009.]]\nThe town is home to [[Gillingham FC|Gillingham F.C.]], who play at [[Priestfield Stadium]] and were first elected to the [[Football League]] in 1920 as members of the new [[Football League Third Division]] (south). They were voted out of the league in 1938, only to be re-elected when the league expanded in 1950. They spent the next 50 years bouncing between the two lower divisions before finally reaching the second tier (then [[Football League First Division|Division One]]) in the 1999\u20132000 season after beating Wigan Athletic in the Play-Off Final at Wembley. They spent five years at this level before being relegated twice, and currently play in [[Football League One|League One]] (third tier), into which they were promoted after winning their first championship for fifty years in the 2012\u201313 season under manager Martin Allen.\n\nThe area boasts a sub-regional sports centre (the Black Lion Leisure Centre, now Medway Park) with three indoor pools for swimming and SCUBA diving, gym, sports hall and squash courts also in the same area is [http://www.trampoline.co.uk Jumpers Rebound Centre] for trampolining a world-famous facility for the sport.\n\nThere is an outdoors sporting centre located at the Strand which provides sailing and motor boat courses for both adults and children. The Strand Leisure Park has an open-air swimming pool on the banks of the River Medway as well as other leisure attractions including tennis courts and a narrow-gauge railway.\n\nGillingham Ice Bowl is the home ice rink for Kent's premier Ice Hockey Club, the [[Invicta Dynamos]], who were originally called the Medway Bears. The Ice Bowl was officially opened by Her Majesty the Queen in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal Visit to Maidstone and the Medway Towns 31 October 1984.|url=http://cityark.medway.gov.uk/query/results/?Mode=Search&SearchMode=explorer&SearchWords=Z4c_MovieBase_04&DateList=&.submit=Submit+Query&Boolean=AND&Results=25&PathList=%2FZ4c_Medway_MovieBase%2F&.cgifields=Verbose&.cgifields=Exact|publisher=cityark.medway.gov.uk|accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Modern Pentathlon World Cup 2010====\n[[File:GillinghamStrand3113.JPG|thumb|right|The open-air swimming pool at The Strand]]\nThe [[Great Lines Heritage Park#Medway Park|Medway Park]] leisure centre (formerly the Black Lion) hosted the [[Modern Pentathlon]] World Cup.<ref name=\"pentathlon.org\">[http://pentathlon.org/media-centre/latest-news/itemlist/category/6-world-cup-medway-2010 Modern Pentathlon website.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818022504/http://pentathlon.org/media-centre/latest-news/itemlist/category/6-world-cup-medway-2010 |date=18 August 2012 }}</ref> In the Women's Final, it was won by [[Amelie Caze]] of France, [[Donata Rimsaite]] of [[Lithuania]] got Silver (2nd place) and [[Mhairi Spence]] of Great Britain got Bronze (3rd place).<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/7579264/Britains-Mhairi-Spence-clinches-bronze-at-Modern-Pentathlon-World-Cup.html Jonathan Liew, \"Britain's Mhairi Spence clinches bronze at Modern Pentathlon World Cup\", ''The Telegraph'', 11 April 2010.]</ref> In the Men's Final, it was won by [[\u00c1d\u00e1m Marosi]] of [[Hungary]], Ondrej Polivka (Czech Republic) got Silver and Alexander Lesun (Russia) claimed the Bronze.<ref name=\"pentathlon.org\"/>\n\n====Modern Pentathlon European Championships 2011====\nThese were also held in Medway Park.<ref>[http://www.whatsonmedway.co.uk/whats-on-search/modern-pentathlon-european-championships-2011-p713891 \"Modern Pentathlon European Championships 2011\", Medway What's On.]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\nAndrei Moiseev (of Russia) got Gold for the Men's Final, Serguei Karyakin (also of Russia) got Silver and Dmytro Kirpulyanskyy (of [[Ukraine]]) got the Bronze. James Cooke of GB was a close fourth.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">[http://www.pentathlon.org/results/competition-results/results/pentathlon/835-senior-european-championships Senior European Championships 2011, Modern Pentathlon.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820010031/http://www.pentathlon.org/results/competition-results/results/pentathlon/835-senior-european-championships |date=20 August 2012 }}</ref>\nIn the Women's Final, [[Lena Schoneborn]] (of Germany) got Gold, [[Adrienn T\u00f3th]] (of [[Hungary]]) got Silver and Victoria Tereshuk (of [[Ukraine]]) claimed Bronze.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==Local media==\n\n===Newspapers===\nLocal newspapers for Gillingham include the ''Medway Messenger'', published by the [[KM Group]]. The area also has free newspapers in the ''Medway Extra'' (KM Group) and ''yourmedway'' ([[KOS Media]]).<br />In 2011, ''[[Medway News]]'' and ''Medway Standard'', both published by Kent Regional News and Media, closed down.\n\n===Radio===\nThe local commercial radio station for Gillingham is [[KMFM Medway]], owned by the KM Group. Medway is also served by community radio station [[Radio Sunlight]]. The area can also receive the county wide stations [[BBC Radio Kent]], [[Heart Kent|Heart]] and [[Gold (radio)|Gold]], as well as many radio stations in [[Essex]] and [[Greater London]].\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Entrance Brompton Academy, Gillingham 7566.jpg|thumb|Brompton Academy (Upbury Manor School), the entrance]]\nThe Gillingham Boys Grammar School, which was opened in 1923,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> later became [[The Howard School, Kent|The Howard School]] in 1975, when it merged with the Rainham Campus secondary school for boys. Other secondary schools include [[Rainham Mark Grammar School]] (formerly the Gillingham Technical School), [[Brompton Academy]] (formerly New Brompton College and before that Upbury Arts College, Upbury Manor), Rainham Girls School, [[Chatham Grammar School for Girls]] and the [[Robert Napier School]]. \nThere are also three primary schools in the small residential area called Twydall: Twydall Infant School, Twydall Junior School and [[St Thomas of Canterbury RC Primary School, Gillingham|St Thomas of Canterbury R.C. School]]. In Gillingham itself are St. Mary's, Barnsole Road, Woodlands, Byron, and Napier Community Primary Schools. In Wigmore, there is the Fairview Infants and Junior Schools and in Hempstead, the Hempstead Infant and Junior Schools.\n\nGillingham also hosts [[MidKent College]], a [[Further Education College]] which introduced Higher Education courses in 2012 and [[Universities at Medway]], a university campus complex comprising [[University of Kent]], [[Canterbury Christ Church University]] and [[University of Greenwich]] on the former [[HMS Pembroke]] barracks buildings.\n\nSee [[List of schools in Medway]] for a full list of schools serving Gillingham and the Medway area.\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St Mary Magdeline Church .jpg|thumb|A view of St Mary Magdeline Church]]\nWithin Gillingham there are many churches from different denominations of Christianity. There are three [[Church of England]] churches: the historic parish church of St. Mary Magdalene; the evangelical St. Mark's; and St. Augustine's. There are also [[Baptist]], [[Methodist]] and Roman Catholic churches.\n\nThe Parish Church of St Mary Magdalene (\"The Church on the Green\",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Horn|first1=Jenni|title=Former MP Ann Widdecombe helps to raise cash for St Mary Madgalene church in Gillingham|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/anns-anecdotes-help-raise-chuch-97707/|accessdate=18 April 2018|work=kentonline.co.uk|date=21 June 2016}}</ref>) is the oldest building in Gillingham and [[Grade II*|Grade II* Listed]].<ref name=listed>{{cite web|title=Church of St Mary Magdalen|url=https://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/101267814-church-of-st-mary-magdalen-gillingham-north-ward |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\nThe [[Normans]] built the church in the early 13th century, then in the 15th century a tower was added. More extensions were added during the 14th century. In 1700, Philip Wightman was commissioned to cast and hang a ring of five bells, to the tower. Then in 1737, [[Richard Phelps (bell-founder)|Richard Phelps]] added another bell to complete a ring of six.<ref name=\"kentpast\">{{cite web|title=History of Gillingham|url=http://www.kentpast.co.uk/Gillingham.html|year=2010|publisher=kentpast.co.uk|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> [[Edward Hasted]] refers to it in 1798, \u2018three isles and three chancels, with a handsome tower steeple at the west end\u2019'.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hasted |first=Edward |date=1798 |title=Parishes |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=63388 |journal=The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |volume=4 |pages=226\u2013249 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> In 1811, Thomas Mears added two treble bells to make eight. In 1868, architect [[Sir Arthur Blomfield]] restored the church and tower and to mark the completion of the restoration, the firm of [[Heaton, Butler and Bayne]] replaced the stained glass in the east window.<ref name=\"kentpast\"/> Based on a design by [[Henry Holiday]].<ref name=listed/>\n\n[[File:Olog church.jpg|thumb|right|A view of Our Lady of Gillingham Catholic Church.]]\nIn 1896, [[Our Lady of Gillingham Church|Our Lady of Gillingham Roman Catholic Church]] was built close to [[Saint Mary Magdalene]] Church, and overlooks the [[River Medway]].\n\nIt followed after other Roman Catholic churches in the area, the closest, [[St Michael]]'s in Chatham (built 1863). Our Lady of Gillingham was built on the town of New Brompton, as Gillingham was then called, to mainly cater for the new workforce \u2013 those employed at [[Chatham Dockyard]]. The church itself was started in 1890, and was completed by 1896, being opened on 12 May 1896.\n\nA local Roman Catholic school was established on the site of the church in 1894. The schoolrooms were used until 1972, when the infant section of the school relocated to nearby Greenfield Road. in 1988, after more building work on the new site, the whole school was reunited on its new site at Greenfield Road. The Church (Our Lady of Gillingham) celebrated its centenary in May 1996, two years after the local school.\n[[File:GillinghamHighSt3949.JPG|left|thumb|St. Mark Church]]\nGillingham also has the J\u0101mi\u2019ah mosque and a Hindu Sabha Mandir.\n\nJames Jershom Jezreel, founder of the Jezreelite sect which flourished in the area during the 19th century, began the building of [[Jezreel's Tower]] on Chatham Hill.  The tower was never completed but stood until its demolition in 1961.  There is still a Jezreels Road off Watling Street.  The tower was painted by Tristram Hillier in 1937 as part of a series of posters for [[Royal Dutch Shell]]. A copy is held in [[Tate Britain]].\n\n==Military==\nBrompton Barracks have long been the home of the [[Royal Engineers]]. Today Gillingham is home to the [[Royal Engineers Museum]], one of the most important for military engineering history.\n\n==Notable people associated with Gillingham==\n{{alumni|residents|date=May 2019}}\n*[[William Adams (sailor, born 1564)|William Adams]] \u2013 nautical adventurer, advisor to [[Tokugawa Ieyasu]], western samurai\n*[[David Bell (VC)|David Bell]] \u2013 [[Victoria Cross]] recipient\n*[[William Cuffay]] \u2013 [[Chartism|chartist]]\n*[[Nicholas Day (actor)|Nicholas Day]] \u2013 actor.\n*[[H. D. Everett]], novelist, born in Gillingham\n*[[David Frost]] \u2013 television presenter.<ref>{{cite ODNB |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-107815 |title=Frost, Sir David Paradine (1939\u20132013) |last=Grade \n|first=Michael |date=12 January 2018 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/107815 |access-date=18 February 2019 |freearticle=y}}</ref>\n*[[Hector Gray]] [[George Cross|GC]] \u2013 [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] officer posthumously awarded the [[George Cross]] for conduct under torture by the Japanese army in 1943.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ww2awards.com/person/534 |title=Hector Bertram Gray |website=WW2 Awards |accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n*[[John Hartnell]] - explorer on [[Franklin's lost expedition]] to find the [[Northwest Passage]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Lost cannibal sailor expedition ship that set sail from Greenhithe in 1845 found in Canada |url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/cannibal-sailors-found-after-more-23214/ |accessdate=6 October 2018 |work=KentOnline |publisher=KM Group 2018 |date=10 September 2014}}</ref>\n*[[David Harvey (geographer)|David Harvey]] \u2013 eminent human geographer.\n*[[Jack Hues]] \u2013 musician, most notably as the lead singer of new wave band Wang Chung\n*[[James Jordan (dancer)|James Jordan]] \u2013 professional dancer, appears on [[Strictly Come Dancing]]\n*[[James McCudden]] \u2013 [[World War I]] [[flying ace]]<ref>{{cite ODNB |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-34694 |title=McCudden, James Thomas Byford (1895\u20131918) |last=Gunby |first=David |date=21 May 2009 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/34694 |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Fernley Marrison]] \u2013 first-class cricketer and British Army officer\n*[[Brian Moore (commentator)|Brian Moore]] \u2013 sport commentator and journalist\n*[[Stel Pavlou]] \u2013 Novelist and screenwriter\n*[[Gary Rhodes]] \u2013 chef and restaurateur\n*[[Vaughan Smith]] \u2013 journalist (founder of Frontline Club), organic farmer who is giving refuge to [[Julian Assange]]\n*[[R. N. Taber]] \u2013 poet and novelist\n*[[Rik Waller]] \u2013 singer, seen on reality TV show \"[[Pop Idol]]\" in 2003.\n*[[Ryan Bertrand]] \u2013 [[UEFA Champions League]] winner with [[Chelsea FC]]\n*[[Dee Murray]] \u2013 bass player with Elton John\n*[[Paul Nihill]] \u2013 Olympic racewalker\n\n==Twin towns==\n* {{flagicon|Japan}} \u2014 [[It\u014d, Shizuoka|Ito]] and [[Yokosuka, Kanagawa|Yokosuka]] (Japan), the latter being the burial place of [[William Adams (sailor, born 1564)|William Adams]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Medway]]\n*[[Strood]]\n*[[Rochester, Kent|Rochester]]\n*[[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]]\n*[[Rainham, Kent|Rainham]]\n*[[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham Football Club]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Gillingham (Kent)}}\n{{commons category|Gillingham, Kent}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100329110819/http://www.medway.gov.uk/medwayimages/ Archive Images]\n\n{{Medway}}\n{{Kent}}\n{{Former non-metropolitan districts of England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Gillingham, Kent| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Kent]]\n[[Category:Former non-metropolitan districts of Kent]]\n[[Category:Unparished areas in Kent]]\n[[Category:Medway]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other places|Gillingham (disambiguation){{!}}Gillingham}}\n{{short description|Town in Kent, England}}\n{{EngvarB|date=June 2013}}\n{{infobox UK place\n|official_name       = Gillingham\n|unitary_england     = [[Medway]]\n|lieutenancy_england = [[Kent]]\n|region              = South East England\n|country             = England\n|coordinates         = {{coord|51.385|0.550|display=inline,title}}\n|static_image_name   = Gillingham High Street (2) - geograph.org.uk - 639121.jpg\n|static_image_caption= High Street, Gillingham\n| population         = 104,157\n| population_ref     = (2011 census, including Rainham and its southern suburbs)<ref>https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/reports/localarea?compare=1119883912</ref>\n|constituency_westminster= [[Gillingham and Rainham (UK Parliament constituency)|Gillingham and Rainham]]\n|post_town           = GILLINGHAM\n|postcode_area       = ME\n|postcode_district   = ME7\n|dial_code           = 01634\n|os_grid_reference   = TQ775675\n|london_distance     = 35.6mi\n}}\n'''Gillingham''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=En-uk-Gillingham(Kent).ogg|\u02c8|d\u0292|\u026a|l|\u026a|\u014b|\u0259m}} {{respell|JIL|ing|\u0259m}}) is a town in the county of [[Kent]] in [[South East England]]. For local government purposes it is also in the [[unitary authority]] of [[Medway]]. The town includes the settlements of [[Brompton, Medway|Brompton]], [[Hempstead, Kent|Hempstead]], [[Wigmore, Kent|Wigmore]], Parkwood, [[Rainham, Medway|Rainham]] which has its own significant retail and leisure hub, Rainham Mark and [[Twydall]].<!-- and [[Lidsing]] is not but used to be in the old Parish of Gillingham -->\n\nGillingham means a \"homestead of Gylla's family\", from [[Old English]] ''ham'' (\"village, homestead\") and ''ingas'' (\"family, followers\"), and was first recorded in the 10th century as ''Gyllingeham''.<ref>Also referred to in old texts as ''Jillyingham Water''.</ref> The town's name is pronounced with a soft 'g', compared to the hard 'g' used for [[Gillingham, Dorset]].\n\n==Status==\nGillingham became an [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] under the [[Local Government Act 1894]], gaining [[municipal borough]] status in 1903.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sharp|first1=Peter|title=Gillingham \u2013 from Rural District to Unitary Authority|url=http://gillinghamcorps.info/history.htm|website=The Salvation Army Gillingham Corps|accessdate=27 September 2015|date=2011}}</ref> John Robert Featherby was the first mayor of the Borough of Gillingham.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Featherby Family Tomb|url=http://www.historicmedway.co.uk/gillingham/st_mary_magdalene_grave_featherby.htm|website=Historic Medway|accessdate=27 September 2015|date=18 June 2012}}</ref> In 1928 [[Rainham, Kent|Rainham]] was added to the Gillingham Borough. Under the [[Local Government Act 1972]] it became a [[non-metropolitan district]]. It merged with the other Medway Towns (in the [[City of Rochester-upon-Medway]] district) in 1998 under the [[Local Government Commission for England (1992)|1990s UK local government reform]], to become part of the [[Medway]] unitary authority.\n\n===Town hall===\nThe Municipal Buildings in Canterbury Street were built as council offices for Gillingham Borough Council. They were opened by the Lord [[Mayor of London]], Sir [[George Broadbridge]], on 25 September 1937. The Lord Mayor was received at [[Gillingham Railway Station (Kent)|Gillingham Railway Station]] by a [[guard of honour]] of boys of [[HMS Arethusa (26)|HMS ''Arethusa'']]. Before the Second World War, air raid sirens were placed on the Municipal Buildings, and the local [[Civil Defence]] headquarters were in a single-storey building, to the rear of the car park. In about 1953, beneath part of the car park, Gillingham Borough Control Centre was built underground.\n\nWhen Gillingham Borough Council later merged with [[Rochester upon Medway]] to form the [[Medway|unitary Medway Authority]] in 1998, the buildings were still used as council offices and for meetings for several years afterwards. Later, Medway Council then moved into the former [[Lloyd's of London]] headquarters at Chatham Gun Wharf, and the Municipal Buildings were considered surplus to requirements. They were sold off in 2008 under a contract which turned them into a residential care home.<ref>John Clancy {{google books|zCD8AwAAQBAJ|Gillingham & Around Through Time|page=46}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe town grew along the road from Brompton on the great lines (military barracks), to the railway station. As such it was a linear development. Close by was the road along the shore line, linking The Strand, and the tiny village of Gillingham Green. Later, communities developed along the top road- Watling street \u2013 turnpike linking Chatham with Dover. All these communities merged into the town that is called today Gillingham.\n\n===Climate===\nGillingham experiences an [[oceanic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Cfb'') similar to almost all of the United Kingdom. Due to its southerly, sheltered, marine position near the European continent  the climate is among the warmest in the whole of England.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Gillingham, Kent 1981\u20132010\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan high C = 8.0\n|Feb high C = 8.1\n|Mar high C = 11.1\n|Apr high C = 13.8\n|May high C = 17.4\n|Jun high C = 20.4\n|Jul high C = 23.3\n|Aug high C = 22.7\n|Sep high C = 20.0\n|Oct high C = 15.7\n|Nov high C = 11.2\n|Dec high C = 8.4\n|year high C = \n|Jan low C = 2.6\n|Feb low C = 2.0\n|Mar low C = 3.9\n|Apr low C = 5.4\n|May low C = 8.3\n|Jun low C = 11.5\n|Jul low C = 13.8\n|Aug low C = 13.7\n|Sep low C = 11.4\n|Oct low C = 8.4\n|Nov low C = 5.2\n|Dec low C = 2.8\n|year low C = \n|Jan precipitation mm = 66.6\n|Feb precipitation mm = 40.5\n|Mar precipitation mm = 40.2\n|Apr precipitation mm = 44.9\n|May precipitation mm = 48.6\n|Jun precipitation mm = 40.9\n|Jul precipitation mm = 38.3\n|Aug precipitation mm = 44.0\n|Sep precipitation mm = 51.2\n|Oct precipitation mm = 60.1\n|Nov precipitation mm = 61.9\n|Dec precipitation mm = 57.0\n|year precipitation mm = \n|Jan rain days = 10.7\n|Feb rain days = 8.6\n|Mar rain days = 9.3\n|Apr rain days = 9.1\n|May rain days = 8.0\n|Jun rain days = 7.8\n|Jul rain days = 7.1\n|Aug rain days = 7.6\n|Sep rain days = 8.4\n|Oct rain days = 10.3\n|Nov rain days = 11.6\n|Dec rain days = 10.6\n|Jan sun = 44.0\n|Feb sun = 64.5\n|Mar sun = 106.8\n|Apr sun = 167.5\n|May sun = 185.1\n|Jun sun = 189.5\n|Jul sun = 208.0\n|Aug sun = 201.2\n|Sep sun = 152.6\n|Oct sun = 120.5\n|Nov sun = 67.7\n|Dec sun = 41.9\n|source 1 = [[Met Office]]<ref>{{cite web\n  | url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/public/weather/climate/gillingham-fc#?tab=climateTables\n  | title=Gillingham FC Climatic Averages 1981\u20132010\n  | publisher=Met Office\n  | accessdate=23 December 2012}}</ref>\n|date=Dec 2012\n}}\n\n==History==\nThe name Gillingham is recorded in the [[Domesday book]] of 1086. It is said to have been named after a warlord, Gyllingas\u2014from the old English ''gyllan'', meaning \"to shout\". He was a notable man in Kent history as he led his warriors into battle screaming and shouting. At the time of the [[Norman Conquest]], Gillingham was a small [[Hamlet (place)|hamlet]]. It was given to the half-brother of [[William I of England]], [[Odo, Bishop of Bayeux]], who rebuilt the parish church at Gillingham and constructed an Archbishop's Palace on land bordered by Grange Road, the ruins of which could still be seen in the last century. Gillingham itself, at the time, was a small hamlet, built around the parish church and surrounded by large farm-holdings, of which St. Mark's Parish formed part, being part of Brittain Farm.\n\n[[William Adams (sailor, born 1564)|William Adams]] mentioned Gillingham in his writings, saying: \"... two English\nmiles from Rochester and one mile from Chatham, where the King's ships do lie\". Adams was baptised at Gillingham Parish Church on 24 September 1564.<ref>WILL ADAMS: Gillingham\u2019s own Samurai.</ref>\n\n[[File:GillinghamStrand3117.JPG|thumb|right|The River Medway estuary at The Strand, Gillingham. The Kingsnorth power stations are on the opposite bank.]] The Strand was once owned by the Davenport family in 1635, the Davenport family included a Mayor of Gillingham,<ref name=amdavenport>[http://cityark.medway.gov.uk/query/results/?Mode=Search&PathList=&SearchWords=de0402_21&DateLis CityArt, Medway Council.] t</ref> pie makers and key holders of Gillingham. The Davenport family had a road named after them in 1920. The Davenport estate was in [[Ashford, Kent]]. The estate comprised around 15000 acres and was called The Davenport Manor. The Davenports lost the estate in 1889. The Davenport family were among the investors in the Chatham Dockyard.\nIn [[medieval]] times the part of Gillingham known as Grange was a limb of the [[Cinque Ports]]<ref>[http://www.medwaymemories.co.uk/?page_id=269 Stephen Rayner, \"A piece of Hastings \u2026 in a corner of Gillingham\", Medway memories.]</ref> and the maritime importance of the area continued until the late 1940s. Indeed, a large part of [[Chatham Dockyard]] lay within Gillingham: the [[dockyard]] started in Gillingham and, until the day it was closed in 1984, two-thirds of the then modern-day dockyard lay within the boundaries of Gillingham. The dockyard was founded by Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] on the site of the present gun wharf, the establishment being transferred to the present site about 1622. In 1667 a Dutch fleet sailed up the [[River Medway]] and, having landed at [[Queenborough]] on the [[Isle of Sheppey]] and laying siege to the fort at [[Sheerness]], invaded Gillingham in what became known as the [[raid on the Medway]]. The Dutch eventually retreated, but the incident caused great humiliation to the [[Royal Navy]].\n\nThe [[Seven Years' War]] began in 1756 and the government immediately gave orders for the defence of the dockyard; by 1758 the Chatham Lines of Defence were built. Over a mile long, they stretched across the neck of the dockyard [[peninsula]], from Chatham Reach, south of the dockyard, across to Gillingham Reach on the opposite side. One of the [[redoubt]]s on the Lines was at [[Fort Amherst|Amherst]]. The batteries faced away from the dockyard itself to forestall an attack from the landward side; the ships and shore-mounted guns on the river were considered sufficient to protect from that side. The lines of defence are now part of the [[Great Lines Heritage Park]] and also the Lower Lines Park (near [[MidKent College]], Gillingham Campus).\n[[File:GillinghamNavalWarMem2707.JPG|thumb|right|[[Chatham Naval Memorial]] on the Gillingham Great Lines]]\nWar with France began again in 1778, and once more it was necessary to strengthen the defences. Fort Amherst was the first to be improved; it was followed by work beginning in 1800 to add others at [[Fort Pitt, Kent|Fort Pitt]], Chatham, plus Fort Delce and [[Fort Clarence]] (both in [[Rochester, Kent|Rochester]]); later in the 19th century others were added, including one at [[Fort Darland]] in Gillingham. Within all these buildings a barracks was built to house the soldiers. All this work, and the expansion of the dockyard, meant that more homes were needed for the workers. The position of the Lines meant that this building could only happen beyond, and so New Brompton came into being. The population rose to 9,000 people by 1851.\n\nGillingham was still only a small village; eventually it, too, was swallowed up, and the name of the whole settlement changed to Gillingham. In the 1891 census its population was 27,809, and in 1901, it was 42,530.\n\nIn 1919, after World War I, a [[Chatham Naval Memorial|naval war memorial]] in the shape of a white stone obelisk was set up on the Great Lines, from where it can be seen for many miles.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Nigel Yates, ''Kent in the Twentieth Century''.</ref> Additional structures were added in 1945 to commemorate the dead of World War II. Similar monuments stand in the dockyard towns of [[Portsmouth]] and [[Plymouth]].\n\nIn 1919 the Frederick Burton family, which owned the old brick works, sold it and migrated to [[Auckland, New Zealand]] with their daughter Edith.\n\n===Disasters===\nGillingham has been the scene of two notable disasters: on 11 July 1929 a public demonstration by Gillingham Fire Brigade [[Gillingham Fair fire disaster|went wrong]], resulting in 15 fatalities;<ref>[http://www.medway.gov.uk/index/leisure/localhistory/timeline/17909/firemanswedding.htm Medway Council: \"Fireman's wedding disaster\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080110173808/http://www.medway.gov.uk/index/leisure/localhistory/timeline/17909/firemanswedding.htm |date=10 January 2008 }}</ref> and in the [[1951 Gillingham bus disaster]], 24 Royal Marine cadets aged 10 to 13 were killed in a road accident.\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Gillingham Bus Depot - geograph.org.uk - 726224.jpg|thumb|[[Arriva Medway Towns]] bus depot in Gillingham]]\nThe main source of employment was at [[Chatham Dockyard]], two-thirds of which lay within the boundaries of Gillingham. When it ceased to be a [[naval base]] in 1984, there was significant unemployment. A [[World Heritage Site]] application is today planned for the Dockyard and its defences.<ref>See www.chathamworldheritage.co.uk</ref> Since the 1980s, Gillingham has rebuilt its economic base and the ''Gillingham Business Park'' was set up {{convert|3|mi|km}} from the town centre, to attract investments and diversify economic activity. The business park is one of the most popular business locations in North [[Kent]] and is located about two miles (3&nbsp;km) north of the [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2 motorway]]. Gillingham has a [[marina]] called ''Gillingham Marina''. Gillingham is an important retail centre serving a substantial part of Medway. The town has a large [[street market]] in the High Street on Saturdays and Mondays, and is the busiest in the whole of Medway.<ref>''Gillingham Town Centre Development Framework''</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Roads===\n\nThe [[Roman road]] now known as [[Watling Street]] passed through Gillingham; and until the opening of the Medway Towns bypass (the [[M2 motorway (Great Britain)|M2 motorway]]) in the mid-1960s the same route was followed by the traffic on the A2 to Dover. That road had been [[toll road|turnpiked]] in 1730, as part of the London\u2013[[Canterbury]] coaching route.\n\nIn June 1996 the [[Medway Tunnel]] opened, giving Gillingham a second link to the M2 and Strood.\n\n===Railways===\n[[File:GillinghamRail3959.JPG|thumb|right|[[Gillingham (Kent) railway station|Gillingham Railway Depot]]]]\nThe [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway]] opened its [[Chatham Main Line|line]] between Chatham and [[Faversham]] on 25 January 1858; and a country station was opened here called New Brompton. This was to serve the dockyard labourers' homes that had sprung up during the [[Napoleonic Wars]]. A branch line led into the dockyard. The station later became [[Gillingham (Kent) railway station|Gillingham Railway Station]].\n\nServices improved significantly when in July 1939,<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Electric Railways \n |publisher='Stendec Systems' \n |year=2007 \n |url=http://www.electric-railways.co.uk/L2_DC_750_CR/1_general/g3_proj/prj-0d75-sr.html \n |accessdate=16 February 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928003510/http://www.electric-railways.co.uk/L2_DC_750_CR/1_general/g3_proj/prj-0d75-sr.html \n |archivedate=28 September 2007 \n}}</ref> Gillingham became the terminus of the [[Railway electrification in Great Britain|electrified]] system of the [[Southern Railway (UK)|Southern Railway]].\n\n===Trams===\nGillingham was served by an electric tram system operated by the [[Chatham and District Light Railways Company]] from 1902 to 1930.<ref name=\"trams\">{{cite book| author=Harley, Robert J.| year=1994| title=Maidstone and Chatham Tramways| publisher=Middleton Press|isbn=1-873793-40-5}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:Gillingham Library - geograph.org.uk - 518041.jpg|thumb|Gillingham Library]]\n\n===Library===\nGillingham Public Library is located in the High Street.\n\n===Sport===\n[[File:GillinghamPriestfields3982.JPG|thumb|right|Priestfield Stadium, Home of the Gills]]\n[[File:The Black Lion Leisure Centre, Mill Rd - geograph.org.uk - 1243346.jpg|right|thumb| A view of former The Black Lion Leisure Centre (Now Medway Park), April 2009.]]\nThe town is home to [[Gillingham FC|Gillingham F.C.]], who play at [[Priestfield Stadium]] and were first elected to the [[Football League]] in 1920 as members of the new [[Football League Third Division]] (south). They were voted out of the league in 1938, only to be re-elected when the league expanded in 1950. They spent the next 50 years bouncing between the two lower divisions before finally reaching the second tier (then [[Football League First Division|Division One]]) in the 1999\u20132000 season after beating Wigan Athletic in the Play-Off Final at Wembley. They spent five years at this level before being relegated twice, and currently play in [[Football League One|League One]] (third tier), into which they were promoted after winning their first championship for fifty years in the 2012\u201313 season under manager Martin Allen.\n\nThe area boasts a sub-regional sports centre (the Black Lion Leisure Centre, now Medway Park) with three indoor pools for swimming and SCUBA diving, gym, sports hall and squash courts also in the same area is [http://www.trampoline.co.uk Jumpers Rebound Centre] for trampolining a world-famous facility for the sport.\n\nThere is an outdoors sporting centre located at the Strand which provides sailing and motor boat courses for both adults and children. The Strand Leisure Park has an open-air swimming pool on the banks of the River Medway as well as other leisure attractions including tennis courts and a narrow-gauge railway.\n\nGillingham Ice Bowl is the home ice rink for Kent's premier Ice Hockey Club, the [[Invicta Dynamos]], who were originally called the Medway Bears. The Ice Bowl was officially opened by Her Majesty the Queen in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal Visit to Maidstone and the Medway Towns 31 October 1984.|url=http://cityark.medway.gov.uk/query/results/?Mode=Search&SearchMode=explorer&SearchWords=Z4c_MovieBase_04&DateList=&.submit=Submit+Query&Boolean=AND&Results=25&PathList=%2FZ4c_Medway_MovieBase%2F&.cgifields=Verbose&.cgifields=Exact|publisher=cityark.medway.gov.uk|accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Modern Pentathlon World Cup 2010====\n[[File:GillinghamStrand3113.JPG|thumb|right|The open-air swimming pool at The Strand]]\nThe [[Great Lines Heritage Park#Medway Park|Medway Park]] leisure centre (formerly the Black Lion) hosted the [[Modern Pentathlon]] World Cup.<ref name=\"pentathlon.org\">[http://pentathlon.org/media-centre/latest-news/itemlist/category/6-world-cup-medway-2010 Modern Pentathlon website.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120818022504/http://pentathlon.org/media-centre/latest-news/itemlist/category/6-world-cup-medway-2010 |date=18 August 2012 }}</ref> In the Women's Final, it was won by [[Amelie Caze]] of France, [[Donata Rimsaite]] of [[Lithuania]] got Silver (2nd place) and [[Mhairi Spence]] of Great Britain got Bronze (3rd place).<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/athletics/7579264/Britains-Mhairi-Spence-clinches-bronze-at-Modern-Pentathlon-World-Cup.html Jonathan Liew, \"Britain's Mhairi Spence clinches bronze at Modern Pentathlon World Cup\", ''The Telegraph'', 11 April 2010.]</ref> In the Men's Final, it was won by [[\u00c1d\u00e1m Marosi]] of [[Hungary]], Ondrej Polivka (Czech Republic) got Silver and Alexander Lesun (Russia) claimed the Bronze.<ref name=\"pentathlon.org\"/>\n\n====Modern Pentathlon European Championships 2011====\nThese were also held in Medway Park.<ref>[http://www.whatsonmedway.co.uk/whats-on-search/modern-pentathlon-european-championships-2011-p713891 \"Modern Pentathlon European Championships 2011\", Medway What's On.]{{dead link|date=November 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\nAndrei Moiseev (of Russia) got Gold for the Men's Final, Serguei Karyakin (also of Russia) got Silver and Dmytro Kirpulyanskyy (of [[Ukraine]]) got the Bronze. James Cooke of GB was a close fourth.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">[http://www.pentathlon.org/results/competition-results/results/pentathlon/835-senior-european-championships Senior European Championships 2011, Modern Pentathlon.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820010031/http://www.pentathlon.org/results/competition-results/results/pentathlon/835-senior-european-championships |date=20 August 2012 }}</ref>\nIn the Women's Final, [[Lena Schoneborn]] (of Germany) got Gold, [[Adrienn T\u00f3th]] (of [[Hungary]]) got Silver and Victoria Tereshuk (of [[Ukraine]]) claimed Bronze.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==Local media==\n\n===Newspapers===\nLocal newspapers for Gillingham include the ''Medway Messenger'', published by the [[KM Group]]. The area also has free newspapers in the ''Medway Extra'' (KM Group) and ''yourmedway'' ([[KOS Media]]).<br />In 2011, ''[[Medway News]]'' and ''Medway Standard'', both published by Kent Regional News and Media, closed down.\n\n===Radio===\nThe local commercial radio station for Gillingham is [[KMFM Medway]], owned by the KM Group. Medway is also served by community radio station [[Radio Sunlight]]. The area can also receive the county wide stations [[BBC Radio Kent]], [[Heart Kent|Heart]] and [[Gold (radio)|Gold]], as well as many radio stations in [[Essex]] and [[Greater London]].\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Entrance Brompton Academy, Gillingham 7566.jpg|thumb|Brompton Academy (Upbury Manor School), the entrance]]\nThe Gillingham Boys Grammar School, which was opened in 1923,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> later became [[The Howard School, Kent|The Howard School]] in 1975, when it merged with the Rainham Campus secondary school for boys. Other secondary schools include [[Rainham Mark Grammar School]] (formerly the Gillingham Technical School), [[Brompton Academy]] (formerly New Brompton College and before that Upbury Arts College, Upbury Manor), Rainham Girls School, [[Chatham Grammar School for Girls]] and the [[Robert Napier School]]. \nThere are also three primary schools in the small residential area called Twydall: Twydall Infant School, Twydall Junior School and [[St Thomas of Canterbury RC Primary School, Gillingham|St Thomas of Canterbury R.C. School]]. In Gillingham itself are St. Mary's, Barnsole Road, Woodlands, Byron, and Napier Community Primary Schools. In Wigmore, there is the Fairview Infants and Junior Schools and in Hempstead, the Hempstead Infant and Junior Schools.\n\nGillingham also hosts [[MidKent College]], a [[Further Education College]] which introduced Higher Education courses in 2012 and [[Universities at Medway]], a university campus complex comprising [[University of Kent]], [[Canterbury Christ Church University]] and [[University of Greenwich]] on the former [[HMS Pembroke]] barracks buildings.\n\nSee [[List of schools in Medway]] for a full list of schools serving Gillingham and the Medway area.\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St Mary Magdeline Church .jpg|thumb|A view of St Mary Magdeline Church]]\nWithin Gillingham there are many churches from different denominations of Christianity. There are three [[Church of England]] churches: the historic parish church of St. Mary Magdalene; the evangelical St. Mark's; and St. Augustine's. There are also [[Baptist]], [[Methodist]] and Roman Catholic churches.\n\nThe Parish Church of St Mary Magdalene (\"The Church on the Green\",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Horn|first1=Jenni|title=Former MP Ann Widdecombe helps to raise cash for St Mary Madgalene church in Gillingham|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/anns-anecdotes-help-raise-chuch-97707/|accessdate=18 April 2018|work=kentonline.co.uk|date=21 June 2016}}</ref>) is the oldest building in Gillingham and [[Grade II*|Grade II* Listed]].<ref name=listed>{{cite web|title=Church of St Mary Magdalen|url=https://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/101267814-church-of-st-mary-magdalen-gillingham-north-ward |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\nThe [[Normans]] built the church in the early 13th century, then in the 15th century a tower was added. More extensions were added during the 14th century. In 1700, Philip Wightman was commissioned to cast and hang a ring of five bells, to the tower. Then in 1737, [[Richard Phelps (bell-founder)|Richard Phelps]] added another bell to complete a ring of six.<ref name=\"kentpast\">{{cite web|title=History of Gillingham|url=http://www.kentpast.co.uk/Gillingham.html|year=2010|publisher=kentpast.co.uk|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> [[Edward Hasted]] refers to it in 1798, \u2018three isles and three chancels, with a handsome tower steeple at the west end\u2019'.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hasted |first=Edward |date=1798 |title=Parishes |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=63388 |journal=The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent |publisher=Institute of Historical Research |volume=4 |pages=226\u2013249 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref> In 1811, Thomas Mears added two treble bells to make eight. In 1868, architect [[Sir Arthur Blomfield]] restored the church and tower and to mark the completion of the restoration, the firm of [[Heaton, Butler and Bayne]] replaced the stained glass in the east window.<ref name=\"kentpast\"/> Based on a design by [[Henry Holiday]].<ref name=listed/>\n\n[[File:Olog church.jpg|thumb|right|A view of Our Lady of Gillingham Catholic Church.]]\nIn 1896, [[Our Lady of Gillingham Church|Our Lady of Gillingham Roman Catholic Church]] was built close to [[Saint Mary Magdalene]] Church, and overlooks the [[River Medway]].\n\nIt followed after other Roman Catholic churches in the area, the closest, [[St Michael]]'s in Chatham (built 1863). Our Lady of Gillingham was built on the town of New Brompton, as Gillingham was then called, to mainly cater for the new workforce \u2013 those employed at [[Chatham Dockyard]]. The church itself was started in 1890, and was completed by 1896, being opened on 12 May 1896.\n\nA local Roman Catholic school was established on the site of the church in 1894. The schoolrooms were used until 1972, when the infant section of the school relocated to nearby Greenfield Road. in 1988, after more building work on the new site, the whole school was reunited on its new site at Greenfield Road. The Church (Our Lady of Gillingham) celebrated its centenary in May 1996, two years after the local school.\n[[File:GillinghamHighSt3949.JPG|left|thumb|St. Mark Church]]\nGillingham also has the J\u0101mi\u2019ah mosque and a Hindu Sabha Mandir.\n\nJames Jershom Jezreel, founder of the Jezreelite sect which flourished in the area during the 19th century, began the building of [[Jezreel's Tower]] on Chatham Hill.  The tower was never completed but stood until its demolition in 1961.  There is still a Jezreels Road off Watling Street.  The tower was painted by Tristram Hillier in 1937 as part of a series of posters for [[Royal Dutch Shell]]. A copy is held in [[Tate Britain]].\n\n==Military==\nBrompton Barracks have long been the home of the [[Royal Engineers]]. Today Gillingham is home to the [[Royal Engineers Museum]], one of the most important for military engineering history.\n\n==Notable people associated with Gillingham==\n{{alumni|residents|date=May 2019}}\n*[[William Adams (sailor, born 1564)|William Adams]] \u2013 nautical adventurer, advisor to [[Tokugawa Ieyasu]], western samurai\n*[[David Bell (VC)|David Bell]] \u2013 [[Victoria Cross]] recipient\n*[[William Cuffay]] \u2013 [[Chartism|chartist]]\n*[[Nicholas Day (actor)|Nicholas Day]] \u2013 actor.\n*[[H. D. Everett]], novelist, born in Gillingham\n*[[David Frost]] \u2013 television presenter.<ref>{{cite ODNB |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-107815 |title=Frost, Sir David Paradine (1939\u20132013) |last=Grade \n|first=Michael |date=12 January 2018 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/107815 |access-date=18 February 2019 |freearticle=y}}</ref>\n*[[Hector Gray]] [[George Cross|GC]] \u2013 [[Royal Air Force|RAF]] officer posthumously awarded the [[George Cross]] for conduct under torture by the Japanese army in 1943.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ww2awards.com/person/534 |title=Hector Bertram Gray |website=WW2 Awards |accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n*[[John Hartnell]] - explorer on [[Franklin's lost expedition]] to find the [[Northwest Passage]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Lost cannibal sailor expedition ship that set sail from Greenhithe in 1845 found in Canada |url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/cannibal-sailors-found-after-more-23214/ |accessdate=6 October 2018 |work=KentOnline |publisher=KM Group 2018 |date=10 September 2014}}</ref>\n*[[David Harvey (geographer)|David Harvey]] \u2013 eminent human geographer.\n*[[Jack Hues]] \u2013 musician, most notably as the lead singer of new wave band Wang Chung\n*[[James Jordan (dancer)|James Jordan]] \u2013 professional dancer, appears on [[Strictly Come Dancing]]\n*[[James McCudden]] \u2013 [[World War I]] [[flying ace]]<ref>{{cite ODNB |url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/10.1093/ref:odnb/9780198614128.001.0001/odnb-9780198614128-e-34694 |title=McCudden, James Thomas Byford (1895\u20131918) |last=Gunby |first=David |date=21 May 2009 |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/34694 |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Fernley Marrison]] \u2013 first-class cricketer and British Army officer\n*[[Brian Moore (commentator)|Brian Moore]] \u2013 sport commentator and journalist\n*[[Stel Pavlou]] \u2013 Novelist and screenwriter\n*[[Gary Rhodes]] \u2013 chef and restaurateur\n*[[Vaughan Smith]] \u2013 journalist (founder of Frontline Club), organic farmer who is giving refuge to [[Julian Assange]]\n*[[R. N. Taber]] \u2013 poet and novelist\n*[[Rik Waller]] \u2013 singer, seen on reality TV show \"[[Pop Idol]]\" in 2003.\n*[[Ryan Bertrand]] \u2013 [[UEFA Champions League]] winner with [[Chelsea FC]]\n*[[Dee Murray]] \u2013 bass player with Elton John\n*[[Paul Nihill]] \u2013 Olympic racewalker\n\n==Twin towns==\n* {{flagicon|Japan}} \u2014 [[It\u014d, Shizuoka|Ito]] and [[Yokosuka, Kanagawa|Yokosuka]] (Japan), the latter being the burial place of [[William Adams (sailor, born 1564)|William Adams]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Medway]]\n*[[Strood]]\n*[[Rochester, Kent|Rochester]]\n*[[Chatham, Kent|Chatham]]\n*[[Rainham, Kent|Rainham]]\n*[[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham Football Club]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Gillingham (Kent)}}\n{{commons category|Gillingham, Kent}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100329110819/http://www.medway.gov.uk/medwayimages/ Archive Images]\n\n{{Medway}}\n{{Kent}}\n{{Former non-metropolitan districts of England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Gillingham, Kent| ]]\n[[Category:Medway]]\n[[Category:Towns in Kent]]\n[[Category:Former non-metropolitan districts of Kent]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Category:Unparished areas in Kent", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gillingham,_Kent"}
{"title_page": "List of children's hospitals", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis is a '''list of [[children's hospital]]s''', [[hospital]]s that specialize in [[pediatrics]].\n\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n{{TOC right}}\n\nA [[children's hospital]] is a hospital that offers its services exclusively to children and adolescents. Most children's hospitals can serve children from birth up to the age of 21.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hardin|first=Amy Peykoff|last2=Hackell|first2=Jesse M.|last3=Medicine|first3=Committee on Practice and Ambulatory|date=2017-09-01|title=Age Limit of Pediatrics|url=https://pediatrics.aappublications.org/content/140/3/e20172151|journal=Pediatrics|language=en|volume=140|issue=3|doi=10.1542/peds.2017-2151|issn=0031-4005|pmid=28827380|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mottchildren.org/news/archive/201709/cs-mott-children%E2%80%99s-hospital-provide-care-all-patients|title=C.S. Mott Children\u2019s Hospital to provide care for all patients through 21st birthday {{!}} CS Mott Children's Hospital {{!}} Michigan Medicine|website=www.mottchildren.org|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.chocchildrens.org/young-adult-childrens-hospital/|title=I'm Not a Kid. Why am I Being Treated at a Children's Hospital?|date=2018-09-11|website=CHOC Children's Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> The number of children's hospitals proliferated in the 20th century, as pediatric medical and surgical specialties separated from internal medicine and adult surgical specialties.\n\nChildren's hospitals are characterized by greater attention to the psychosocial support of children and their families. Some children and young people have to spend relatively long periods in the hospital, so having access to play and teaching staff can also be an important part of their care. With local partnerships, this can include trips to local botanical gardens, the zoo, and public libraries, for instance.\n\nIn addition to psychosocial support, children's hospitals have the added benefit of being staffed by professionals who are trained in treating children. A medical doctor that undertakes vocational training in pediatrics must also be accepted for membership by a professional college before they can practice pediatrics. While many normal hospitals can treat children adequately, pediatric specialists may be a better choice when it comes to treating rare afflictions that may prove fatal or severely detrimental to young children, in some cases before birth. Also, many children's hospitals will continue to see children with rare illnesses into adulthood, allowing for a continuity of care.\n\n==International==\n* [[Shriners Hospitals for Children]], North America\n\n==Argentina==\n\n===Ciudad Aut\u00f3noma de Buenos Aires===\n* Hospital Italiano de Buenos Aires\n* [[Hospital Garrahan|Garrahan Pediatric Hospital]]\n* Hospital de Ni\u00f1os R. Gutierrez\n* Hospital Pedro de Elizalde ex Casa Cuna\n\n===Cordoba===\n* Children's Hospital of the Holy Trinity\n* Pediatric Hospital of the Child Jesus\n\n===Tucuman===\n* Hospital del Ni\u00f1o Jesus\n\n==Australia==\n\n===Australian Capital Territory===\n* [[Centenary Hospital for Women and Children]], Canberra\n\n===Queensland===\n* [[Queensland Children's Hospital]], Brisbane\n* [[Mater Health Services|Mater Childrens Hospital]] (former children's hospital in Brisbane)\n* [[Royal Children's Hospital, Herston]] (former children's hospital in Brisbane)\n\n===New South Wales===\n* [[John Hunter Children's Hospital]], [[Newcastle, New South Wales|Newcastle]]\n* [[Royal Alexandra Hospital for Children]], [[Westmead, New South Wales|Westmead]]\n* [[Sydney Children's Hospital]], [[Randwick, New South Wales|Randwick]]\n\n===South Australia===\n* [[Women's and Children's Hospital, Adelaide|Women's and Children's Hospital]], [[Adelaide]]\n\n===Victoria===\n* [[Monash Children's Hospital]], [[Clayton, Victoria|Clayton]]\n* [[Royal Children's Hospital]], [[Parkville, Victoria|Parkville]]\n\n===Western Australia===\n* [[Perth Children's Hospital]]\n\n==Austria==\n* [[Anna-Kinderspital]], former children's hospital in [[Graz]]\n* [[Gottfried von Preyer\u2019sches Kinderspital]], Vienna\n* [[Karolinen-Kinderspital]], former children's hospital in Vienna\n* [[Kinderklinik Glanzing]], [[Vienna]], integrated into Wilhelminenspital\n* [[Kindersanatorium Sonnegg]], Hirschegg ([[Vorarlberg]])\n* [[Landes-Kinderkrankenhaus]], [[Linz]]\n* [[Leopoldst\u00e4dter Kinderspital]], former children's hospital in Vienna\n* [[Mautner Markhof\u2019sches Kinderspital]], former children's hospital in Vienna\n* [[St. Anna Kinderspital]], Vienna\n* [[Sankt-Josef-Kinderspital]], former children's hospital in Vienna\n\n==Belgique==\n*{{ill|H\u00f4pital universitaire des enfants Reine Fabiola|fr}}\n\n==Bangladesh==\n* Aurobindo Childrens Hospital,Bangladesh\n\n===Chittagong===\n* Chittagong Maa-Shishu O General Hospital, Agrabad, Chittagong\n\n===Dhaka===\n* [[Dhaka Shishu Hospital]]\n\n==Brazil==\n\n===S\u00e3o Paulo===\n* [[HIS - Hospital Infantil Sabar\u00e1]]\n\n===Curitiba===\n* [[HPP - Hospital Pequeno Pr\u00edncipe]]\n\n===Fortaleza===\n* [[HIAS - Hospital Infantil Albert Sabin]]\n\n===Recife===\n* [[IMIP - Instituto Materno-Infantil Professor Fernando Figueira]]\n\n=== Porto Alegre ===\n\n* [[Hospital da Crian\u00e7a Santo Ant\u00f4nio]]\n\n==Canada==\n\n===Alberta===\n*[[Alberta Children's Hospital]], [[Calgary]]\n*[[Stollery Children's Hospital]], [[Edmonton]]\n\n===British Columbia===\n* [[British Columbia Children's Hospital]], [[Vancouver]]\n\n===Manitoba===\n* [[Winnipeg General Hospital|The Children's Hospital of Winnipeg]], [[Winnipeg]]\n\n===Newfoundland and Labrador===\n* [[Janeway Children's Health and Rehabilitation Centre]], [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]]\n\n===Nova Scotia===\n* [[IWK Health Centre]], [[Halifax Urban Area|Halifax]]\n\n===Ontario===\n* [[Children's Hospital at