{short description|NCAA-sanctioned post-season college football bowl game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Collegebowl\n| name                = Famous Idaho Potato Bowl\n| full_name           = \n| nickname            = \n| defunct             =\n| logo                = Image:Famous Idaho Potato Bowl logo.jpg\n| image_size          = 250px \n| caption             =  \n| stadium             = [[Albertsons Stadium]]\n| previous_stadiums   = \n| location            = [[Boise, Idaho]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| previous_locations  = \n| years               = 1997\u2013present\n| previous_tie-ins    = [[Big West Conference|Big West]] (1997\u20132000)<br />[[Conference USA|C-USA]] (1997\u20131999)<br/>[[Western Athletic Conference|WAC]] (2000\u20132012)<br />[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] (2001\u20132008)<br />\n| conference_tie-ins  = [[Mountain West Conference|MWC]], [[Mid-American Conference|MAC]]\n| payout              = 800,000 (2019 season)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.collegefootballpoll.com/bowl-schedule/2019/ |title=2019 Bowl Schedule |website=collegefootballpoll.com |accessdate=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n| sponsors            = Humanitarian Bowl Association (1997\u20131998)<br />[[Crucial Technology]] (1999\u20132003)<br />[[MPC Computers]] (2004\u20132006)<br />[[Roady's Truck Stops]] (2007\u20132009)<br />uDrove (2010)<br />[[Idaho Potato Commission]] (2011\u2013present)\n| former_names        = Sports Humanitarian Bowl (1997)<br />Humanitarian Bowl (1998)<br />Crucial.com Humanitarian Bowl (1999\u20132003)<br />MPC Computers Bowl (2004\u20132006)<br />Roady's Humanitarian Bowl (2007\u20132009)<br />uDrove Humanitarian Bowl (2010)\n| prev_matchup_year   = 2018\n| prev_matchup_season = 2018\n| prev_matchup_teams  = [[2018 BYU Cougars football team|BYU]] vs [[2018 Western Michigan Broncos football team|Western Michigan]] \n| prev_matchup_score  = BYU 49\u201318\n| next_matchup_year   = 2019 season\n| next_matchup_season = 2019\n| next_matchup_teams  = [[2019 Nevada Wolf Pack football team|Nevada]] vs. [[2019 Ohio Bobcats football team|Ohio]] ([[2020 Famous Idaho Potato Bowl|Ohio 30\u201321]])\n| next_matchup_date   = <!--embedded above, due to January date-->\n}}\nThe '''Famous Idaho Potato Bowl''', previously the '''Humanitarian Bowl''' (1997\u20132003, 2007\u20132010) and the '''MPC Computers Bowl''' (2004\u20132006), is an [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]-sanctioned post-season [[college football]] [[bowl game]] that has been played annually since 1997 at [[Albertsons Stadium]] on the campus of [[Boise State University]] in [[Boise, Idaho|Boise]], [[Idaho]]. The game is televised nationally on the [[ESPN]] family of networks. [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]] defeated [[Utah State Aggies football|Utah State]] in the inaugural game in [[1997 Humanitarian Bowl|1997]].\n\n==History==\n===Conference tie-ins===\nThe Humanitarian Bowl was launched in part to give the [[Big West Conference]] a bowl to send its champion to.<ref name=bptpbg>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=frReAAAAIBAJ&sjid=BTAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=6184%2C980674 |newspaper=Lewiston Morning Tribune |location=(Idaho)|title=Boise planning to push bowl game to NCAA |date=April 19, 1997 |page=2B}}</ref> From 1982 until the end of the 1996 season, the Big West champion faced the winner of the [[Mid-American Conference]] (MAC) championship in a bowl; this was the [[California Bowl]] until 1991 and the [[Las Vegas Bowl]] afterward. After the 1996 game the Las Vegas Bowl renegotiated its contract, forcing both conferences to look for other options. This led to the creation of the Humanitarian Bowl as well as the creation of the [[Detroit]]-based [[Motor City Bowl]], where the MAC was to send its champion.\n\nFrom 1997 to 1999, the Big West champion was matched with a team from [[Conference USA]] (C-USA), while in 2000 the [[Western Athletic Conference]] (WAC) sent a representative. The Big West stopped sponsoring football after the 2000 season, and bowl organizers extended a permanent invite to the WAC to replace the Big West as host of the game, and struck an agreement with the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC) to provide a [[Bowl eligibility|bowl-eligible]] team if it had yet to fill its bowl allotment. The WAC champion would receive the automatic bid to the game unless that team received a better offer from another bowl game or qualified for the [[Bowl Championship Series]] (BCS).\n\nThe WAC and ACC met in the 2001 through 2008 editions of the bowl, except for 2002 when the ACC's slot was filled by [[Iowa State Cyclones football|Iowa State]] of the [[Big 12 Conference]]. In 2009, the [[Mountain West Conference]] was to provide a team, but Mountain West champion [[TCU Horned Frogs football|TCU]] was selected for the [[2010 Fiesta Bowl|Fiesta Bowl]] and the conference did not have enough bowl-eligible teams to send a replacement; as a result, [[Bowling Green Falcons football|Bowling Green]] of the [[Mid-American Conference]] (MAC) was invited. In 2010, the bowl inherited the MAC's [[International Bowl]] tie-in after that [[Toronto]]-based bowl folded; the bowl featured a MAC vs. WAC matchup through 2012.\n\nAfter the WAC stopped sponsoring football in 2012, Mountain West inherited its spot as host, reaching agreement with the bowl to provide a team, starting with the December 2013 edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://denver.sbnation.com/2012/12/15/3769946/famous-idaho-potato-bowl-2013-mountain-west |title=Famous Idaho Potato Bowl will be Mountain West partner in 2013 - SB Nation Denver |publisher=Denver.sbnation.com |date= |accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref> The bowl featured MAC vs. Mountain West matchups in the 2013 through 2015 games. In 2016, the bowl invited in-state [[Idaho Vandals football|Idaho]] of the [[Sun Belt Conference]] in place of a MAC team. The 2017 edition returned to MAC vs. Mountain West, while in the 2018 edition, [[NCAA Division I FBS independent schools|independent]] [[BYU Cougars football|BYU]] was invited in place of a Mountain West team. In late July 2019, it was announced that the Mountain West and Mid-American Conferences would maintain their tie-ins to the bowl through the 2025\u201326 football season.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Season(s) || colspan=2 | Conferences\n|-\n! Host || Opponent\n|-\n| 1997\u20131999 || rowspan=2 | Big West || C-USA\n|-\n| 2000 || WAC\n|-\n| 2001 || rowspan=4 | WAC || ACC\n|-\n| 2002 || Big 12\n|-\n| 2003\u20132008 || ACC\n|-\n| 2009\u20132012 || rowspan=2 | MAC <!-- opponent -->\n|-\n| 2013\u20132015 || rowspan=3 | Mountain West <!-- host -->\n|-\n| 2016 || Sun Belt <!-- opponent -->\n|-\n| 2017 || rowspan=3 | MAC <!-- opponent -->\n|-\n| 2018 || Independent <!-- host -->\n|-\n| 2019 || Mountain West <!-- host -->\n|}\n\n===Sponsors===\nThe game was sponsored by [[Micron Technology]], an Idaho-based manufacturer, from 1999 to 2002 under the name Crucial.com, which sold computer memory upgrades from Micron. The bowl game then briefly had no sponsor for the January 2004 game. In December 2004, the name was changed to the '''MPC Computers Bowl'''. [[MPC Computers]], which is also based in Idaho, was formerly MicronPC, the computer manufacturing division of Micron, but was later split off as a separate company. In April 2007, it was announced that the bowl would again be called the Humanitarian Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idahostatesman.com/104/story/80015.html |title=Boise, Meridian, Nampa, Caldwell news by Idaho Statesman |publisher=Idahostatesman.com |date= |accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref> In May 2007, Boise-based [[Roady's Truck Stops]] was announced as the new sponsor, thus renaming the game the '''Roady's Humanitarian Bowl'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=2887632 |title=Humanitarian bowl teams up with Idaho-based truck stop chain - College Football - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=May 30, 2007 |accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref> On May 25, 2010, [[uDrove]], a maker of applications for the transportation industry, became the sponsor of the Humanitarian Bowl, signing a four-year agreement to replace Roady's.<ref>[http://www.ktvb.com/sports/Humanitarian-Bowl-changing-title-sponsor-to-uDrove-94770359.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530091938/http://www.ktvb.com/sports/Humanitarian-Bowl-changing-title-sponsor-to-uDrove-94770359.html |date=May 30, 2010 }}</ref> On August 3, 2011, the [[Idaho Potato Commission]] (IPC) signed a six-year naming rights deal to sponsor the bowl, renaming it the '''Famous Idaho Potato Bowl'''.<ref>[http://newsblaze.com/story/2011080313010300004.pnw/topstory.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111125021435/http://newsblaze.com/story/2011080313010300004.pnw/topstory.html |date=November 25, 2011 }}</ref> In December 2017, IPC announced that they would be sponsoring the bowl for an additional five years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thepacker.com/article/ipc-sponsor-potato-bowl-five-more-years |title=IPC to sponsor Potato Bowl five more years |first=Daniel |last=Vanderhorst |website=thepacker.com |date=December 29, 2017 |accessdate=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe game is the longest running cold weather bowl game currently in operation. The payout is $750,000, but teams are required to provide a corporate sponsor, purchase a minimum number of tickets, and stay at a selected hotel for a minimum stay. Because of this, 7\u20134 [[2001 UCLA Bruins football team|UCLA]] declined an invitation to the 2001 Humanitarian Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://uclabruins.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120301aab.html |title=UCLA Addresses Bowl Situation - Statement from UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=October 15, 2007 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120719155218/http://uclabruins.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120301aab.html |archive-date=July 19, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Highway Angel===\nFrom 2008 through 2012, bowl organizers, in conjunction with the Truckload Carriers Association, featured a \"Highway Angel of the Year\" to game attendees. Highway Angels are [[truck driver]]s who performed a heroic feat to save the life of another motorist.\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n! Year\n! Honoree\n! style=\"width: 80%; | Description\n|-\n| 2008\n| Leonard T. Roach\n| Roach pulled a driver from a water-filled ditch near [[South Bend, Indiana]], even though the [[wind chill factor]] was {{convert|-20|\u00b0F|\u00b0C}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truckload.org/index.asp?bid=1445&archiveyear=2008&nid=89 |title=ESPN will Broadcast Heroic Trucking Story to Millions of Non-Trucking Viewers |publisher=Truckload.org |date=December 19, 2008 |accessdate=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2009\n| Michael Hunt\n| Hunt used his truck to push away a vehicle (and its driver) from a fiery collision near [[Spring Lake, North Carolina]], which had already claimed the life of the other driver.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truckload.org/index.asp?bid=1445&archiveyear=2009&nid=130 |title=Selfless Truck Driver to Be Honored as \"2009 Highway Angel of the Year\" |publisher=Truckload.org |date=December 14, 2009 |accessdate=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2010\n| Shawn L. Hubbard\n| While driving his truck near [[Diamond Bar, California]], Hubbard came upon a fiery car crash in which the driver was deceased, but the passenger was still alive and trapped in the burning car. Hubbard freed the passenger and pulled him from the vehicle just moments before it was completely engulfed in flames.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truckload.org/index.asp?bid=1445&archiveyear=2010&nid=206 |title=TCA's Highway Angel of the Year to Share Moment in Spotlight with Motorist He Saved |publisher=Truckload.org |date=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2011\n| Marcus Beam\n| While driving near [[Benson, North Carolina]], Beam observed a speeding car strike another vehicle, causing the second car to overturn and roll down an embankment. While other motorists watched without offering help, Beam freed the female driver from the wreckage, and pulled two small children from the mangled vehicle as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truckload.org/index.asp?bid=1445&archiveyear=2011&nid=265 |title=Marcus Beam to Receive 2011 Highway Angel of the Year Trophy at the Famous Idaho Potato Bowl in Boise, Idaho |publisher=Truckload.org |date=December 14, 2011 |accessdate=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2012\n| Kenny Cass\n| While driving in [[Portland, Oregon]], Cass witnessed a pick-up truck rear-end a 53' tractor trailer and become wedged up to its windshield under the trailer. Cass made the scene safe by placing emergency triangles on the road, freed the pick-up truck driver from his vehicle while smoke billowed from beneath the truck and tended to the drivers wounds until emergency personnel arrived 20 minutes later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.truckload.org/index.asp?bid=1445&archiveyear=2012&nid=332 |title=Truckload Carriers Association Selects Highway Angel of the Year |publisher=Truckload.org |date=December 3, 2012 |accessdate=May 19, 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Game results== \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#29AAE3; color:#FFFFFF; border: 2px solid #FED74E;\"|No.\n! style=\"background:#29AAE3; color:#FFFFFF; border: 2px solid #FED74E;\"|Date\n! style=\"background:#29AAE3; color:#FFFFFF; border: 2px solid #FED74E;\"|Bowl name\n! style=\"background:#29AAE3; color:#FFFFFF; border: 2px solid #FED74E;\" colspan=2| Winning Team\n! style=\"background:#29AAE3; color:#FFFFFF; border: 2px solid #FED74E;\" colspan=2| Losing Team\n! style=\"background:#29AAE3; color:#FFFFFF; border: 2px solid #FED74E;\"|Attnd.\n|-\n| align=center|1 || December 29, 1997 || [[1997 Humanitarian Bowl|Humanitarian Bowl]] || '''[[1997 Cincinnati Bearcat