{"title_page": "2014 Tokyo Marathon", "text_new": "{{Infobox athletics competition\n|competition = 8th Tokyo Marathon\n|image = 2014 Tokyo marathon mass race.jpg\n|caption = Runners in the 2014 Tokyo Marathon mass race\n|venue = [[Tokyo]], Japan\n|dates = 23 February\n|gold = [[Dickson Chumba]] (2:05:42 '''CR''')<br>[[Tirfi Tsegaye]] (2:22:23 '''CR''')\n|prev = [[2013 Tokyo Marathon|2013]]\n|next = [[2015 Tokyo Marathon|2015]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2014 [[Tokyo Marathon]]''' ({{lang-ja|\u6771\u4eac\u30de\u30e9\u30bd\u30f3 2014}}) was the eighth edition of the annual [[marathon]] race in [[Tokyo]], Japan and was held on Sunday, 23 February. An [[IAAF Gold Label Road Race]], it was the first [[World Marathon Majors]] event to be held that year and represented the second occasion that the Tokyo race was part of the elite-level marathon series.\n\nBoth elite race winners set new course records: [[Dickson Chumba]] ran a men's record of 2:05:42 and [[Tirfi Tsegaye]]'s run of 2:22:23 was a women's record.\n\n==Pre-race build up==\nFollowing on from the Tokyo Marathon's induction into the World Marathon Majors circuit, high calibre and international fields were invited for the men's and women's elite races. In the men's race, invitees included [[Tadese Tola]] (2013 world medallist), [[Abel Kirui]] (a two-time world champion), [[Peter Some]] (2013 [[Paris Marathon]] winner), [[Dickson Chumba]] (2013 [[Eindhoven Marathon]] winner), and former Tokyo champion [[Michael Kipyego]]. In total, seven of the invited men's field had personal bests faster than two hours and six minutes.<ref name=PM1>Minshull, Phil (2014-01-23). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/tokyo-marathon-iaaf-gold-label-road-race 2014 Tokyo Marathon releases elite fields, course records under threat]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.</ref> [[Arata Fujiwara]] was the most prominent domestic starter.<ref name=KN1>Nakamura, Ken (2014-02-21). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/preview/tokyo-marathon-preview-tadese-tola-lucy-kabuu Course records expected at Tokyo Marathon]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.</ref>\n\nIn the women's division, [[Lucy Wangui Kabuu]] was the fastest entrant with her best of 2:19:34 hours. Second fastest was Japan's [[Yoko Shibui]] (2:19:41) although the 35-year-old was not expected to reach her past performance. A group of Ethiopian women were among the other prominent entrants, including [[Tirfi Tsegaye]], [[Atsede Baysa]], [[Birhane Dibaba]] and [[Merima Mohammed]].<ref name=PM1/><ref name=KN1/>\n\n==Results==\n[[Dickson Chumba]] of Kenya won the men's race in a course record time of 2:05:42 hours. This also made it the fastest time ever recorded in the city, bettering [[Gert Thys]]'s record of 2:06:33 set at the defunct [[Tokyo International Marathon]]. In the women's race, Ethiopia's [[Tirfi Tsegaye]] topped the podium with a course record of 2:22:23 hours \u2013 an improvement of over three minutes on the previous record.<ref>Nakamura, Ken (2014-02-23). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/tokyo-marathon-dickson-chumba-tirfi-tsegaye Chumba and Tsegaye break course records at Tokyo Marathon]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.</ref><ref>Larner, Brett (2014-02-23). [http://japanrunningnews.blogspot.co.uk/2014/02/chumba-and-tsegaye-set-tokyo-marathon.html Chumba and Tsegaye Set Tokyo Marathon CRs as Five Japanese Men Break 2:10]. Japanese Running News. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.</ref>  \nThe [[wheelchair race]]s had mainly domestic entrants and [[Hiroyuki Yamamoto (athlete)|Hiroyuki Yamamoto]] and [[Wakako Tsuchida]] were the best of the men's and women's divisions, respectively.\n\n===Men===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"  style=\"font-size:95%;\" width=50%\n! width=\"10%\"| Position \n! width=\"40%\"| Athlete \n! width=\"30%\"| Nationality\n! width=\"20%\"|Time\n|-\n|  align=center|[[Image:Gold medal icon.svg]]  || [[Dickson Chumba]] || {{KEN}} || 2:05:42 {{AthAbbr|CR}} {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n|  align=center|[[Image:Silver medal icon.svg]]  || [[Tadese Tola]] || {{ETH}} || 2:05:57\n|-\n|  align=center|[[Image:Bronze medal icon.svg]]  || [[Sammy Kitwara]] || {{KEN}} || 2:06:30\n|-\n| align=center|4 || [[Michael Kipyego]] || {{KEN}} || 2:06:58\n|-\n| align=center|5 || [[Peter Kimeli Some]] || {{KEN}} || 2:07:05\n|-\n| align=center|6 || [[Geoffrey Kipsang]] || {{KEN}} || 2:07:37\n|-\n| align=center|7 || [[Deressa Chimsa]] || {{ETH}} || 2:07:40\n|-\n| align=center|8 || [[Kohei Matsumura]] || {{JPN}} || 2:08:09 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n| align=center|9 || [[Koji Kobayashi (athlete)|Koji Kobayashi]] || {{JPN}} || 2:08:51 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n| align=center|10 || [[Abel Kirui]] || {{KEN}} || 2:09:04\n|-\n| align=center|11 || [[Hirokatsu Kurosaki]] || {{JPN}} || 2:09:07 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n| align=center|12 || [[Masanori Sakai]] || {{JPN}} || 2:09:10 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|}\n;Other notable performers\n*[[Cyrus Njui]]: 14th (2:09:35)\n*[[Abderrahime Bouramdane]]: 16th (2:12:09)\n*[[Mekubo Mogusu]]: 25th (2:16:43)\n*[[Arata Fujiwara]]: 76th (2:30:58)\n*[[Yared Asmerom]]: DNF\n\n===Women===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"  style=\"font-size:95%;\" width=50%\n! width=\"10%\"| Position \n! width=\"40%\"| Athlete \n! width=\"30%\"| Nationality\n! width=\"20%\"|Time\n|-\n| align=center|[[Image:Gold medal icon.svg]]  || [[Tirfi Tsegaye]] || {{ETH}} || 2:22:23 {{AthAbbr|CR}}\n|-\n| align=center|[[Image:Silver medal icon.svg]]  || [[Birhane Dibaba]] || {{ETH}} || 2:22:30 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n| align=center|[[Image:Bronze medal icon.svg]]  || [[Lucy Wangui Kabuu]] || {{KEN}} || 2:24:16\n|-\n| align=center|4 || [[Caroline Rotich]] || {{KEN}} || 2:24:35\n|-\n| align=center|5 || [[Janet Rono]] || {{KEN}} || 2:26:03 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n| align=center|6 || [[Albina Mayorova]] || {{RUS}} || 2:28:18\n|-\n| align=center|7 || [[Mai Ito]] || {{JPN}} || 2:28:36\n|-\n| align=center|8 || [[Rika Shintaku]] || {{JPN}} || 2:31:15 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n| align=center|9 || [[Manami Kamitanida]] || {{JPN}} || 2:31:34 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n| align=center|10 || [[Hiroko Yoshitomi]] || {{JPN}} || 2:32:38\n|-\n| align=center|11 || [[Azusa Nojiri]] || {{JPN}} || 2:33:39\n|-\n| align=center|12 || [[Atsede Baysa]] || {{ETH}} || 2:35:03\n|}\n;Other notable performers\n*[[Yoko Shibui]]: 85th (3:11:05)\n*[[Olena Shurkhno]]: DNF\n*[[Merima Mohammed]]: DNF\n\n===Wheelchair men===\n[[File:2014 Tokyo Marathon wheelchair race.jpg|thumb|Competitors in the women's wheelchair marathon race]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"  style=\"font-size:95%;\" width=40%\n! width=\"10%\"| Position \n! width=\"40%\"| Athlete \n! width=\"30%\"| Nationality\n! width=\"20%\"|Time\n|-\n| align=center|[[Image:Gold medal icon.svg]]  || [[Hiroyuki Yamamoto (athlete)|Hiroyuki Yamamoto]] || {{JPN}} || 1:30:43\n|-\n| align=center|[[Image:Silver medal icon.svg]]  || [[Soejima Masazumi]] || {{JPN}} || 1:30:44\n|-\n| align=center|[[Image:Bronze medal icon.svg]]  || [[Horano-jo Kota]] || {{JPN}} || 1:34:45\n|}\n\n===Wheelchair women===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"  style=\"font-size:95%;\" width=40%\n! width=\"10%\"| Position \n! width=\"40%\"| Athlete \n! width=\"30%\"| Nationality\n! width=\"20%\"|Time\n|-\n| align=center|[[Image:Gold medal icon.svg]]  || [[Wakako Tsuchida]] || {{JPN}} || 1:48:08\n|-\n| align=center|[[Image:Silver medal icon.svg]]  || [[Kazumi Nakayama]] || {{JPN}} || 2:04:05\n|-\n| align=center|[[Image:Bronze medal icon.svg]]  || [[Koki Mizuki]] || {{JPN}} || 2:07:35\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Race results\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140325021107/http://www.tokyo42195.org/2014/press/files/140223_04_man_top500r.pdf Results 2014 Tokyo Marathon Man] {{in lang|ja}}. Tokyo Marathon. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140325015356/http://www.tokyo42195.org/2014/press/files/140223_05_woman_top500r.pdf Results 2014 Tokyo Marathon Woman] {{in lang|ja}}. Tokyo Marathon. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140325020039/http://www.tokyo42195.org/2014/press/files/140223_06_man_wr.pdf Results \u30de\u30e9\u30bd\u30f3\u8eca\u3044\u3059\u7537\u5b50\uff0fMarathon:Wheelchair(Men)] {{in lang|ja}}. Tokyo Marathon. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140325021144/http://www.tokyo42195.org/2014/press/files/140223_07_woman_wr.pdf Results \u30de\u30e9\u30bd\u30f3\u8eca\u3044\u3059\u5973\u5b50\uff0fMarathon:Wheelchair(Women)] {{in lang|ja}}. Tokyo Marathon. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140325021334/http://www.tokyo42195.org/2014_en/ Official website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140325020951/http://www.tokyo42195.org/2014/press/files/140223_num_runners.pdf Participation data] {{in lang|ja}}\n{{Tokyo Marathon}}\n{{World Marathon Majors 2014}}\n\n[[Category:2014 in Japanese sport|Tokyo Marathon]]\n[[Category:2014 marathons|Tokyo]]\n[[Category:2014 in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:February 2014 sports events in Asia|Tokyo Marathon]]\n[[Category:Tokyo Marathon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox athletics competition\n|competition = 8th Tokyo Marathon\n|image = 2014 Tokyo marathon mass race.jpg\n|caption = Runners in the 2014 Tokyo Marathon mass race\n|venue = [[Tokyo]], Japan\n|dates = 23 February\n|gold = [[Dickson Chumba]] (2:05:42 '''CR''')<br>[[Tirfi Tsegaye]] (2:22:23 '''CR''')\n|prev = [[2013 Tokyo Marathon|2013]]\n|next = [[2015 Tokyo Marathon|2015]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2014 [[Tokyo Marathon]]''' ({{lang-ja|\u6771\u4eac\u30de\u30e9\u30bd\u30f3 2014}}) was the eighth edition of the annual [[marathon]] race in [[Tokyo]], Japan and was held on Sunday, 23 February. An [[IAAF Gold Label Road Race]], it was the first [[World Marathon Majors]] event to be held that year and represented the second occasion that the Tokyo race was part of the elite-level marathon series.\n\nBoth elite race winners set new course records: [[Dickson Chumba]] ran a men's record of 2:05:42 and [[Tirfi Tsegaye]]'s run of 2:22:23 was a women's record.\n\n==Pre-race build up==\nFollowing on from the Tokyo Marathon's induction into the World Marathon Majors circuit, high calibre and international fields were invited for the men's and women's elite races. In the men's race, invitees included [[Tadese Tola]] (2013 world medallist), [[Abel Kirui]] (a two-time world champion), [[Peter Some]] (2013 [[Paris Marathon]] winner), [[Dickson Chumba]] (2013 [[Eindhoven Marathon]] winner), and former Tokyo champion [[Michael Kipyego]]. In total, seven of the invited men's field had personal bests faster than two hours and six minutes.<ref name=PM1>Minshull, Phil (2014-01-23). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/news/tokyo-marathon-iaaf-gold-label-road-race 2014 Tokyo Marathon releases elite fields, course records under threat]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.</ref> [[Arata Fujiwara]] was the most prominent domestic starter.<ref name=KN1>Nakamura, Ken (2014-02-21). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/preview/tokyo-marathon-preview-tadese-tola-lucy-kabuu Course records expected at Tokyo Marathon]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.</ref>\n\nIn the women's division, [[Lucy Wangui Kabuu]] was the fastest entrant with her best of 2:19:34 hours. Second fastest was Japan's [[Yoko Shibui]] (2:19:41) although the 35-year-old was not expected to reach her past performance. A group of Ethiopian women were among the other prominent entrants, including [[Tirfi Tsegaye]], [[Atsede Baysa]], [[Birhane Dibaba]] and [[Merima Mohammed]].<ref name=PM1/><ref name=KN1/>\n\n==Results==\n[[Dickson Chumba]] of Kenya won the men's race in a course record time of 2:05:42 hours. This also made it the fastest time ever recorded in the city, bettering [[Gert Thys]]'s record of 2:06:33 set at the defunct [[Tokyo International Marathon]]. In the women's race, Ethiopia's [[Tirfi Tsegaye]] topped the podium with a course record of 2:22:23 hours \u2013 an improvement of over three minutes on the previous record.<ref>Nakamura, Ken (2014-02-23). [http://www.iaaf.org/news/report/tokyo-marathon-dickson-chumba-tirfi-tsegaye Chumba and Tsegaye break course records at Tokyo Marathon]. IAAF. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.</ref><ref>Larner, Brett (2014-02-23). [http://japanrunningnews.blogspot.co.uk/2014/02/chumba-and-tsegaye-set-tokyo-marathon.html Chumba and Tsegaye Set Tokyo Marathon CRs as Five Japanese Men Break 2:10]. Japanese Running News. Retrieved on 2014-03-24.</ref>  \nThe [[wheelchair race]]s had mainly domestic entrants and [[Hiroyuki Yamamoto (athlete)|Hiroyuki Yamamoto]] and [[Wakako Tsuchida]] were the best of the men's and women's divisions, respectively.\n\n===Men===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"  style=\"font-size:95%;\" width=50%\n! width=\"10%\"| Position \n! width=\"40%\"| Athlete \n! width=\"30%\"| Nationality\n! width=\"20%\"|Time\n|-\n|  align=center|[[Image:Gold medal icon.svg]]  || [[Dickson Chumba]] || {{KEN}} || 2:05:42 {{AthAbbr|CR}} {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n|  align=center|[[Image:Silver medal icon.svg]]  || [[Tadese Tola]] || {{ETH}} || 2:05:57\n|-\n|  align=center|[[Image:Bronze medal icon.svg]]  || [[Sammy Kitwara]] || {{KEN}} || 2:06:30\n|-\n| align=center|4 || [[Michael Kipyego]] || {{KEN}} || 2:06:58\n|-\n| align=center|5 || [[Peter Kimeli Some]] || {{KEN}} || 2:07:05\n|-\n| align=center|6 || [[Geoffrey Kipsang]] || {{KEN}} || 2:07:37\n|-\n| align=center|7 || [[Deressa Chimsa]] || {{ETH}} || 2:07:40\n|-\n| align=center|8 || [[Kohei Matsumura]] || {{JPN}} || 2:08:09 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n| align=center|9 || [[Koji Kobayashi (athlete)|Koji Kobayashi]] || {{JPN}} || 2:08:51 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n| align=center|10 || [[Abel Kirui]] || {{KEN}} || 2:09:04\n|-\n| align=center|11 || [[Hirokatsu Kurosaki]] || {{JPN}} || 2:09:07 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|-\n| align=center|12 || [[Masanori Sakai]] || {{JPN}} || 2:09:10 {{AthAbbr|PB}}\n|}\n;Other notable performers\n*[[Cyrus Njui]]: 14th (2:09:35)\n*[[Abderrahime Bouramdane]]: 16th (2:12:09)\n*[[Mekubo Mogusu]]: 25th (2:16:43)\n*[[Arata Fujiwara]]: 76th (2:30:58)\n*[[Yared Asmerom]]: DNF\n\n===Women===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"